{"term":"1967","caseName":"Cameron v. Johnson","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1967/699","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - March 06, 1968","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren15/oral_argument_audio/15076","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"John Earl Cameron et al., appellant, versus Paul Johnson and so forth et al.","start":0,"stop":8.271,"duration":8.27},{"text":"Mr. Kinoy, you may continue your argument.","start":8.271,"stop":12.151,"duration":3.88}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, yesterday afternoon, we were discussing the constitutional implications of the opened concession of Mississippi that the statute here under consideration has been selectively enforced in the area of free expression.","start":12.151,"stop":32.573,"duration":20.42},{"text":"Here, Mississippi has openly acknowledged that if a parade which completely obstructs a street has general community approval, the statute will not be enforced.","start":32.573,"stop":51.02,"duration":18.45},{"text":"But if it has a different purpose, perhaps one in sharp opposition to what this Court has called in Button, the opinions of the politically dominant White community, the statute will be enforced.","start":51.02,"stop":69.11,"duration":18.09}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Where is that concession?","start":69.11,"stop":71.176,"duration":2.07}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"That concession is directly in the record, Mr. Justice Black at page -- it's set forth in full on page 74 in our brief.","start":71.176,"stop":81.846,"duration":10.67},{"text":"The excerpts from the transcript are on page 74 of our brief.","start":81.846,"stop":86.68,"duration":4.83}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Showing the concession?","start":86.68,"stop":87.753,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, open complete concession.","start":87.753,"stop":91.036,"duration":3.28},{"text":"Now, what Mississippi attempts to do here is precisely what Louisiana attempted to do before this Court in Cox and that is the effort to say that a parade is not a mass demonstration but as this Court there pointed out, a parade as the dictionary itself had -- a mass demonstration as the dictionary itself points out is a public manifestation of feeling.","start":91.036,"stop":124.439,"duration":33.4},{"text":"Now, if this public manifestation of feeling expresses safe, dominant community views, then it's permissible.","start":124.439,"stop":136.076,"duration":11.64},{"text":"If it expresses unpopular views such as opposition to the dominant majorities, disenfranchisement of Negroes, then it is semantically a mass demonstration prohibited by the statute, but this is precisely what this Court time and time again has said that the Constitution prohibits.","start":136.076,"stop":164.949,"duration":28.87},{"text":"And as we pointed out yesterday, there has been striking unanimity in this Court on the vice of discriminatory enforcement because as Mr. Justice Black said in his concurring opinion in Cox that discriminatory enforcement represents censorship in its most odious form unconstitutional under the First and Fourteenth Amendment.","start":164.949,"stop":195.282,"duration":30.33}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, Mr. Kinoy, is it also that they could not get the cases tried fairly in the courts of Mississippi?","start":195.282,"stop":202.957,"duration":7.67}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"Did they concede that?","start":202.957,"stop":204.304,"duration":1.35}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Yeah.","start":204.304,"stop":204.405,"duration":0.1}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"No, they did not concede that, sir.","start":204.405,"stop":206.479,"duration":2.07},{"text":"They conceded that the statute was selectively enforced, completely selectively enforced and the -- yes, Mr. Justice.","start":206.479,"stop":217.119,"duration":10.64}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Was there any statement comparable to the statement on page 74 of your brief with respect to the blocking of access to courthouses?","start":217.119,"stop":230.19,"duration":13.07},{"text":"It's the first part of the statute here under which these people are prosecuted relates to blocking courthouses and public buildings.","start":230.19,"stop":240.628,"duration":10.44},{"text":"The second part of it relates to free use of the streets.","start":240.628,"stop":246.316,"duration":5.69},{"text":"The -- what you have referred to as a concession as it appears on page 74 as I read it relates only to blocking the streets.","start":246.316,"stop":258.13,"duration":11.81},{"text":"Now, is there anything like that with respect to blocking access to public buildings or courthouses?","start":258.13,"stop":264.511,"duration":6.38}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":264.511,"stop":265.166,"duration":0.65},{"text":"On page 236 of the transcript on the examination of Mr. Dukes and solicitor in respect to the homecoming parade for Mississippi Southern, the question was asked, “Did the parade pass in front of the courthouse?”","start":265.166,"stop":281.001,"duration":15.83},{"text":"It did.","start":281.001,"stop":283.108,"duration":2.11},{"text":"The question, “was it during daylight hours?”","start":283.108,"stop":285.146,"duration":2.04},{"text":"Answer, “During the daylight hours.”","start":285.146,"stop":287.912,"duration":2.77},{"text":"Question, “When the courthouse was normally open for business?”","start":287.912,"stop":290.844,"duration":2.93},{"text":"A, “normally open for business.”","start":290.844,"stop":293.009,"duration":2.17},{"text":"Question, “Did it keep people from being able to cross the street from the Sears Roebuck to the courthouse?","start":293.009,"stop":299.402,"duration":6.39},{"text":"Answer, “It did,” so that there is equal concession, Mr. Justice Fortas, in respect to blocking the courthouse.","start":299.402,"stop":309.69,"duration":10.29},{"text":"Now, I suggest to the Court that the only possible conclusion from these open record concessions is that concededly Mississippi is not engaging in the evenhanded enforcement of the statute which the utterly majority of this Court required as a constitutional minimal protection.","start":309.69,"stop":341.387,"duration":31.7},{"text":"And that if federal judicial protection is not available where admittedly there is no evenhanded enforcement of a state statute, then I suggest to the Court the somber warning of the dissent in utterly must be carefully reconsidered.","start":341.387,"stop":365.772,"duration":24.38},{"text":"This is one of the most classic examples which a transcript has ever brought before this Court of planned prosecutorial misuse of a statute regulating freedom of expression.","start":365.772,"stop":381.326,"duration":15.55},{"text":"This is one of the two types of challenges to a state criminal statute which Mr. Justice White pointed out in his dissenting opinion in the original Cameron case warrants extraordinary federal intervention in a state criminal proceeding.","start":381.326,"stop":401.169,"duration":19.84},{"text":"Now, I would suggest to the Court that this pattern of selective enforcement raises a second consideration which emerged sharply at the remand hearing which likewise invokes the criteria of Dombrowski.","start":401.169,"stop":420.864,"duration":19.69},{"text":"Now, this Court has taught us in a numerable opinion that the danger of selective enforcement often flows from statutes overly broad or vague in the area of the First Amendment such a statute is now clearly before this Court.","start":420.864,"stop":444.259,"duration":23.4},{"text":"At the remand hearing, the appellees introduced an amended statute and it's there exhibit at 104 of the appendix House Bill 114 which is now before this Court for consideration for the first time.","start":444.259,"stop":466.396,"duration":22.14},{"text":"This is a wholly different statute now than the statute which was before the Court on the original Cameron consideration and the difference is dramatically summarized in the new title of the statute which is an act to prohibit unreasonable interference with free ingress to and from any public buildings, premises, courthouses, public streets and sidewalks, and the word as the Court will notice unreasonably is now inserted into the text of the statute so that it prohibits picketing or mass demonstrations which unreasonably obstruct or interfere.","start":466.396,"stop":520.386,"duration":53.99},{"text":"Now, I would like to point out to the Court that while this statute was approved on July 9, 1964 by a legislature, it was not called to the attention of the original three-judge court or to the appellants or to this Court on the original review so that the opinions dissenting in Cameron of both Mr. Justice Black and Mr. Justice White deal only with the original text of this statute.","start":520.386,"stop":555.208,"duration":34.82},{"text":"Only on the remand hearing was the amended statute called to the attention of the three-judge court and the appellants, plaintiff below, and --","start":555.208,"stop":568.009,"duration":12.8}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, what's the significance of the amendment?","start":568.009,"stop":569.764,"duration":1.75},{"text":"I didn't catch that.","start":569.764,"stop":570.59,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"The significance of the amendment, Mr. Justice Brennan, is that on the face of the statute, what is prohibited now is not obstruction or interference but unreasonable obstruction or interference and I would suggest --","start":570.59,"stop":590.881,"duration":20.29}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"You say that's vague, is that --","start":590.881,"stop":591.988,"duration":1.11}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":591.988,"stop":593.329,"duration":1.34},{"text":"Now, this raises -- yes.","start":593.329,"stop":595.538,"duration":2.21}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"That's the exact -- precise word that's used in the Fourth Amendment of the Constitution itself.","start":595.538,"stop":602.528,"duration":6.99}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly right, Your Honor.","start":602.528,"stop":603.915,"duration":1.39},{"text":"And Judge Coleman raised that question in the majority opinion below.","start":603.915,"stop":609.413,"duration":5.5}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"That's not a question; that's a fact.","start":609.413,"stop":611.041,"duration":1.63}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, and I would suggest that that illustrates sharply why the vice of unconstitutional vagueness is here present because as Your Honor pointed out for this Court in the recent search and seizure opinion in this term, the word unreasonable in the Fourth Amendment except as Your Honor pointed out, with certain few well-defined exceptions meant that you could not give to a police officer the right to determine what was an unreasonable search or seizure but quite to the contrary, it was a duty of an independent magistrate to rule in advance on an application for a warrant as the Katz case.","start":611.041,"stop":658.619,"duration":47.58},{"text":"The word unreasonable in the --","start":658.619,"stop":660.135,"duration":1.52}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's because of other provisions in the Fourth Amendment which states that no warrant shall issue except upon probable cause.","start":660.135,"stop":665.876,"duration":5.74}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"I would -- I would suggest You Honor that we have the precise problem here.","start":665.876,"stop":669.622,"duration":3.75},{"text":"What's the word unreasonable introduced into the face of the statute does?","start":669.622,"stop":674.911,"duration":5.29},{"text":"It does what Mr. Justice Black suggests in his concurring opinion in Cox.","start":674.911,"stop":680.733,"duration":5.82},{"text":"It gives to the policemen on the beat the power to decide to make the decision on the basis of what he believes subjectively is reasonable or unreasonable whether or not given picketing or whether or not given demonstrating is prohibited by the statute.","start":680.733,"stop":706.146,"duration":25.41},{"text":"This is --","start":706.146,"stop":707.31,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not quite sure I understand the chronology here, Mr. Kinoy.","start":707.31,"stop":711.066,"duration":3.76},{"text":"At the time of these arrests, did the statute read as it now does or as it formally did.","start":711.066,"stop":717.678,"duration":6.61}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"As it formally did.","start":717.678,"stop":719.682,"duration":2},{"text":"It was amended on July 4th.","start":719.682,"stop":722.417,"duration":2.74}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Well then --","start":722.417,"stop":723.585,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"July 9th, I believe it was.","start":723.585,"stop":724.931,"duration":1.35}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Under -- under what statute would these people be prosecuted?","start":724.931,"stop":729.108,"duration":4.18}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"These particular prosecutions are under the original statute.","start":729.108,"stop":734.786,"duration":5.68},{"text":"The relief we seek is injunctive and declaratory judgment relief against the original and now amended statute.","start":734.786,"stop":746.742,"duration":11.96}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I guess --","start":746.742,"stop":747.077,"duration":0.34}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"The court below, Mr. Justice Stewart, took judicial notice of the amended statute and the amended statute was the statute before the Court on remand below.","start":747.077,"stop":757.693,"duration":10.62},{"text":"So that statute I would suggest is of course properly here.","start":757.693,"stop":761.675,"duration":3.98}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"These prosecutions however of your present clients would be under the original statute.","start":761.675,"stop":766.925,"duration":5.25}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, Mr. Justice Stewart.","start":766.925,"stop":768.323,"duration":1.4}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"But your injunction asks what?","start":768.323,"stop":770.21,"duration":1.89},{"text":"Not only the -- that these prosecutions be enjoined but that all future prosecutions of any kind under the statute be --","start":770.21,"stop":776.515,"duration":6.3}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":776.515,"stop":777.132,"duration":0.62},{"text":"That this statute under Dombrowski -- that this statute now as written -- see, we acknowledge, Mr. Justice Stewart, that there is a sharp division in the Court and below on the facial constitutional issue as to the original statute.","start":777.132,"stop":801.524,"duration":24.39},{"text":"That was perfectly clear in the dissenting opinion on the remand and the difference of opinion expressed by Judge Rives below and the opinions of Mr. Justice Black and Mr. Justice White.","start":801.524,"stop":813.307,"duration":11.78},{"text":"We suggest that no such difference of opinion can exist today as to the amended statute, that whatever differences existed before now totally vague and why?","start":813.307,"stop":829.906,"duration":16.6},{"text":"Because --","start":829.906,"stop":829.993,"duration":0.09}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I suppose -- excuse me, Mr. Kinoy, but I suppose it's at least arguable that the insertion of the word “unreasonably” in the 1964 Amendment can really make any substantial difference because there is an element of judgment in the other statutory word whether a particular activity constitutes obstructing or interfering with free ingress or regress.","start":829.993,"stop":861.926,"duration":31.93}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"Precisely, Mr. Justice Stewart.","start":861.926,"stop":863.919,"duration":1.99},{"text":"Our position is, and the record bears it out, that Mississippi interpreted the original statute as if it gave the arresting officer the huge undefined leeway which the word “unreasonable” now clearly gives it.","start":863.919,"stop":884.768,"duration":20.85}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Sir, you don't really make much point of the existence or the non-existence of the word “unreasonably” in the statute.","start":884.768,"stop":893.244,"duration":8.48}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"The only point, Mr. Justice Fortas, is that we say now that Mississippi has made it very clear what their intention was.","start":893.244,"stop":900.973,"duration":7.73},{"text":"Their intention was to write a sweeping overbroad and vague statute.","start":900.973,"stop":907.134,"duration":6.16},{"text":"They made it perfectly clear in their amendment.","start":907.134,"stop":909.885,"duration":2.75},{"text":"And as a matter of fact, the transcript which we had set out for the Court's convenience on page 86 and 87 of our brief points out this extraordinary discussion between the county solicitor and the examining attorney where the county solicitor Mr. Dukess in discussing how he would enforce, the statute says the question -- and these are his words -- the question of what is reasonable I believe, Mr. Smith, is one that people differ on.","start":909.885,"stop":948.795,"duration":38.91},{"text":"But this is the heart of the problem of vagueness in the First Amendment area because such a statute as Mr. Justice Black said in Cox does not provide for government by clearly defined laws but rather for Government by the moment to moment opinions --","start":948.795,"stop":970.777,"duration":21.98}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Is it possible in your judgment to have a statute that prohibits blocking ingress or regress to public buildings or to streets that were not the subject to that infirmity?","start":970.777,"stop":987.489,"duration":16.71}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"I think it might be possible, Mr. Justice Fortas.","start":987.489,"stop":989.804,"duration":2.31},{"text":"I think it would have to be a very carefully drawn -- I think it would have to be very, very carefully drawn with very, very careful limitations.","start":989.804,"stop":998.799,"duration":9}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"How would you phrase it?","start":998.799,"stop":1001.264,"duration":2.47}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that would be a little difficult at this moment for me to phrase fully, Mr. Justice Fortas.","start":1001.264,"stop":1005.492,"duration":4.23},{"text":"I'd want to write it out --","start":1005.492,"stop":1006.118,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Phrase -- phrase it partly for me.","start":1006.118,"stop":1011.003,"duration":4.88}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I -- I would put it in its negative, if I may, Justice Fortas.","start":1011.003,"stop":1015.739,"duration":4.74},{"text":"I would say that I would make sure that this statute guaranteed the opportunity for full expression of First Amendment rights under reasonable conditions but that conditions were spelled out so that a policeman doesn't make the determination.","start":1015.739,"stop":1038.645,"duration":22.91}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"You don't really mean that word, do you?","start":1038.645,"stop":1041.127,"duration":2.48},{"text":"Reasonable, would you let that go in --","start":1041.127,"stop":1043.223,"duration":2.1}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, I wouldn't put it in my statute.","start":1043.223,"stop":1044.885,"duration":1.66},{"text":"I would spell out the criteria precisely, and that's what I would suggest that this Court in the Edwards case in Mr. Justice Stewart's opinion warrants so sharply against, that if such a statute is to be written, it must be precise.","start":1044.885,"stop":1063.067,"duration":18.18}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"I know, but would you or would you not agree that merely because people are exercising the right of free speech, they do not have a total immunity to block what goes on in the public buildings or even the block access to public buildings?","start":1063.067,"stop":1086.368,"duration":23.3}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"I would --","start":1086.368,"stop":1086.467,"duration":0.1}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Would you or would you not agree?","start":1086.467,"stop":1087.887,"duration":1.42}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"I would agree with that, Mr. Justice Fortas, and that problem is not here presented in this case.","start":1087.887,"stop":1093.646,"duration":5.76},{"text":"As this case quite clearly shows the precise -- precisely reversed situation, precisely reversed.","start":1093.646,"stop":1102.31,"duration":8.66}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand you do agree if the federal government somehow -- or the states somehow protected that public building like this one, like the Court is being held from having people come up and block access to it.","start":1102.31,"stop":1120.651,"duration":18.34}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"I agree with that, Mr. Justice Black.","start":1120.651,"stop":1122.415,"duration":1.76},{"text":"I also agree as you have pointed out --","start":1122.415,"stop":1124.225,"duration":1.81}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"So you agree to that?","start":1124.225,"stop":1125.347,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"I agree to that.","start":1125.347,"stop":1126.167,"duration":0.82},{"text":"I also agree that the fundamental values of the First Amendment must always be fully protected and that on a record as this where people in the first place where a statute is not being evenhandedly enforced, it must fall that secondly whereas Judge Rives points out in his opinion below and has the record so clearly indicates and as Mississippi concedes, these peaceful demonstrators, Negro and white citizens calling for the vindication of their most fundamental constitutional federal rights are walking in the very spot in which law enforcement officers for two months have told them it was proper to walk that under those conditions --","start":1126.167,"stop":1187.114,"duration":60.95}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That you want to say that the officer has the right to decide for himself where there's a problem for them to walk there.","start":1187.114,"stop":1194.563,"duration":7.45}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"I would say, Your Honor, that when county officials have for two months blocked of a certain -- if you would look at the diagram which Judge Rives of course has attached to his dissenting opinion which is in the record, a diagram of the Forrest County courthouse, if for two months county officials have said that this is the area in which if you walk here it does not obstruct the main entrance to the courthouse that yes, under Cox and every other opinion of this Court, it would be as this Court has said indefensible entrapment in the area of the First Amendment to say that after that pattern of time, it's permissible to enforce a criminal sanction against people peacefully expressing their views.","start":1194.563,"stop":1260.705,"duration":66.14}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Kinoy, excuse me.","start":1260.705,"stop":1261.493,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And you would hold that -- you would say that officers, deputy chairs or policemen and so forth cannot decide for himself whether it's reasonable for them to do it, cannot make any law by telling them they can come in, but he can -- to bar it, but he can make it a law to say you can come in.","start":1261.493,"stop":1286.004,"duration":24.51}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh no, he can't make it a law.","start":1286.004,"stop":1287.53,"duration":1.53},{"text":"That law was made when the Bill of Rights, Your Honor, was adopted.","start":1287.53,"stop":1293.289,"duration":5.76},{"text":"The law which sanctioned the demonstrations was the First Amendment to the Constitution of the United States.","start":1293.289,"stop":1301.736,"duration":8.45},{"text":"That's the law that says that people have the right to peacefully assemble, express themselves, and petition their government for regress of grievances.","start":1301.736,"stop":1313.206,"duration":11.47}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But it doesn't say that they have the right to -- which the state cannot prevent to march up and down the streets that are dedicated to travelers.","start":1313.206,"stop":1322.851,"duration":9.65}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"No, but it does say that the state may not say some people can do it and other people may not.","start":1322.851,"stop":1328.723,"duration":5.87}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That's a different issue.","start":1328.723,"stop":1329.866,"duration":1.14}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"That's -- and that's the issue, Mr. Justice Black.","start":1329.866,"stop":1332.404,"duration":2.54},{"text":"This case presents --","start":1332.404,"stop":1334.424,"duration":2.02}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"I didn't -- perhaps I misunderstand, Mr. Kinoy, but this conduct at the entrance or near the entrance to the courthouse had been going on for several weeks with the, at least implicit if not explicit permission of the --","start":1334.424,"stop":1350.639,"duration":16.21}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"Two months, Your Honor.","start":1350.639,"stop":1351.096,"duration":0.46}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"-- local authorities for two months.","start":1351.096,"stop":1353.242,"duration":2.15},{"text":"Then, what caused the change, as I understand it, was the enactment of this statute by the legislature of Mississippi.","start":1353.242,"stop":1359.73,"duration":6.49}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly right.","start":1359.73,"stop":1360.478,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"And this statute was then read to these people after it was enacted.","start":1360.478,"stop":1366.181,"duration":5.7},{"text":"A copy was sent down to this place and they copied, and this law was read to these people.","start":1366.181,"stop":1371.633,"duration":5.45},{"text":"They were told about it and they were told, “Now, this is illegal.","start":1371.633,"stop":1375.333,"duration":3.7},{"text":"Now, disperse.”","start":1375.333,"stop":1376.145,"duration":0.81},{"text":"Isn't that it?","start":1376.145,"stop":1377.085,"duration":0.94},{"text":"This wasn't something just a change of mind by the police as you replied, was it?","start":1377.085,"stop":1381.579,"duration":4.49}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"No, and we're all precisely --","start":1381.579,"stop":1382.655,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"This was the enactment of a law by the legislature of Mississippi, wasn't it?","start":1382.655,"stop":1386.378,"duration":3.72}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"And Mr. Justice Stewart, that's precisely our point because the enactment of the law was designed as the Court said in Brown against Louisiana was designed and had the actual effect of stopping and cutting off otherwise peaceful --","start":1386.378,"stop":1405.068,"duration":18.69}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Of making it illegal --","start":1405.068,"stop":1406.131,"duration":1.06}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"Making it illegal to engage --","start":1406.131,"stop":1406.355,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"-- to block ingress into the courthouse.","start":1406.355,"stop":1408.485,"duration":2.13},{"text":"Until then it had not been illegal.","start":1408.485,"stop":1410.615,"duration":2.13},{"text":"Until then, the police would have been taking the law in their own hands of they had arrested these people for blocking it presumably.","start":1410.615,"stop":1417.333,"duration":6.72},{"text":"After the legislator -- the legislature passed the law, the police told these people about the passage of the law, said it's now illegal, now disperse.","start":1417.333,"stop":1425.953,"duration":8.62},{"text":"Isn't that it?","start":1425.953,"stop":1426.962,"duration":1.01}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"Ah!","start":1426.962,"stop":1427.712,"duration":0.75},{"text":"But what --","start":1427.712,"stop":1428.359,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"These -- these are just the offset of police action.","start":1428.359,"stop":1431.719,"duration":3.36},{"text":"This is legislative action --","start":1431.719,"stop":1433.395,"duration":1.68}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"Which I would suggest --","start":1433.395,"stop":1434.245,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"-- of which the enforcement officers told these people, isn't that correct?","start":1434.245,"stop":1436.47,"duration":2.23}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"Which I would suggest, Mr. Justice Stewart, makes this situation doubly serious because it's extremely interesting.","start":1436.47,"stop":1444.103,"duration":7.63},{"text":"Judge Coleman in his findings of fact said that up until April 10th when the first arrest took place, the picketing was peaceful and protected activities.","start":1444.103,"stop":1464.247,"duration":20.14},{"text":"On examination, Mr. Dukes said that if the law had been in effect prior to April 10, the demonstrators would have been guilty of violating the law.","start":1464.247,"stop":1478.807,"duration":14.56},{"text":"In other words, the law itself was designed to cut off peaceful, protected activities.","start":1478.807,"stop":1491.006,"duration":12.2}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"I can't find that in the language of the Section 1 of the law that was passed.","start":1491.006,"stop":1495.177,"duration":4.17},{"text":"It simply it's illegal to -- among other things to block egress or ingress in a public building, including a courthouse.","start":1495.177,"stop":1505.721,"duration":10.54}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"But what the transcript below shows, Mr. Justice Stewart, is what this Court pointed out in Button was so important in considering the operation of a statute, its setting and the way it operated.","start":1505.721,"stop":1522.208,"duration":16.49},{"text":"Let me make this suggestion, Mr. Justice Stewart.","start":1522.208,"stop":1526.038,"duration":3.83},{"text":"I would suggest that it's rather amazing that the majority below and the appellees do not discuss the arrests which took place on the afternoon of April 10 and the morning of April 11 and the morning of May 18.","start":1526.038,"stop":1550.067,"duration":24.03},{"text":"They simply do not discuss them.","start":1550.067,"stop":1551.624,"duration":1.56},{"text":"Why?","start":1551.624,"stop":1552.798,"duration":1.17},{"text":"Because these arrests were of seven people, seven people with not a single bit of evidence in the record.","start":1552.798,"stop":1565.473,"duration":12.67},{"text":"They didn't even attempt to show obstruction of anything whatsoever.","start":1565.473,"stop":1571.018,"duration":5.55},{"text":"And as Judge Rives points out below, he uses the word “fantastic”.","start":1571.018,"stop":1577.952,"duration":6.93},{"text":"He says it's incredibly fantastic to believe that the arrests of seven people carrying signs saying “Mississippians are Americans, too” and “We demand the right to vote” could conceivably be the violation of any state law.","start":1577.952,"stop":1598.07,"duration":20.12},{"text":"Now, we suggest that this is highly significant because this shows the way in which the Mississippi authorities utilized the statute, assuming Mr. Justice Stewart, which we do not because the Court is aware of our position of challenging the facial unconstitutionality of the statute, both originally and as amended, particularly as amended.","start":1598.07,"stop":1624.484,"duration":26.41},{"text":"But assuming a valid statute here, under the second branch of Dombrowkski, I would suggest that nothing is clearer as Judge Rives points out a pattern of utilization of a conceivably valid state statute to harass the exercise of Civil rights and First Amendment activities.","start":1624.484,"stop":1652.828,"duration":28.34}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Kinoy, wasn't there some statute in Mississippi prior to the indictment of this one that would have made blocking access to courthouses unlawful?","start":1652.828,"stop":1664.93,"duration":12.1}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":1664.93,"stop":1666.012,"duration":1.08},{"text":"There were probably ten statutes --","start":1666.012,"stop":1668.212,"duration":2.2}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you have those cited in your brief?","start":1668.212,"stop":1671.22,"duration":3.01},{"text":"You can just tell me yes or no.","start":1671.22,"stop":1672.393,"duration":1.17},{"text":"I don't want to --","start":1672.393,"stop":1673.213,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, they are in the brief, Mr. Justice Fortas and they're also cited in the Court's opinion in Peacock.","start":1673.213,"stop":1679.92,"duration":6.71},{"text":"There are a whole host of statutes which were available to the Mississippi authorities, which if these individuals were really blocking the ingress to that courthouse before the enactment of this statute, could have been invoked by the Mississippi authorities.","start":1679.92,"stop":1696.913,"duration":16.99}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Which court's opinion at Peacock or which Peacock --","start":1696.913,"stop":1700.329,"duration":3.42}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"I think yours, Mr. Justice Stewart.","start":1700.329,"stop":1702.736,"duration":2.41},{"text":"I think the charges which the Peacock --","start":1702.736,"stop":1706.587,"duration":3.85}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, I cited all those charges, yes.","start":1706.587,"stop":1707.061,"duration":0.47}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"The plaintiffs who are being removed on, yes.","start":1707.061,"stop":1709.659,"duration":2.6},{"text":"You cited them sir, I believe, in your opinion.","start":1709.659,"stop":1712.654,"duration":2.99},{"text":"Now, what we would suggest is that the record shows in light now that Mississippi has in fact interpreted the statute as if it had an overbroad sweep bringing into its orbit protected First Amendment and civil rights activities, that the full criteria of Dombrowski under both the first branch and the second branch are met.","start":1712.654,"stop":1750.379,"duration":37.72},{"text":"The only point I would like to make to the Court in conclusion is that what is most serious here is the final suggestion of the majority below that federal relief should be denied because picketing in Mississippi to obtain a vote and to encourage others to do so is a thing of the past.","start":1750.379,"stop":1775.962,"duration":25.58},{"text":"And I would suggest to the Court that as the coroner commission report pointed out just two days ago, country stands at a crossroads, that at this moment in Mississippi and throughout the nation, a strengthening of federal power to protect the peaceful utilization of First Amendment liberties in the solution of fundamental problems which rift this nation is the highest duty and obligation of this Court.","start":1775.962,"stop":1814.2,"duration":38.24},{"text":"That to deny relief today in this case would be to advocate the higher responsibility of the federal national judiciary.","start":1814.2,"stop":1825.153,"duration":10.95},{"text":"Thank you, Your Honor.","start":1825.153,"stop":1826.55,"duration":1.4}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Wells.","start":1826.55,"stop":1836.697,"duration":10.15}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":1836.697,"stop":1841.651,"duration":4.95},{"text":"Please pardon me but I've got -- I'm just getting over a pretty bad cold and I've got a little laryngitis.","start":1841.651,"stop":1847.342,"duration":5.69},{"text":"I'll try not to let it interfere too much.","start":1847.342,"stop":1854.381,"duration":7.04},{"text":"I regret that Mr. Smith yesterday in all most of the beginning of his argument saw fit to go outside the record and take a verbal salvo at the south and Mississippi particularly.","start":1854.381,"stop":1881.794,"duration":27.41},{"text":"He said to this Court conditions are still bad in the south and particularly in Mississippi and we need every vehicle to protect people's federal rights.","start":1881.794,"stop":1896.998,"duration":15.2},{"text":"He added just last night that there was a shooting in Mississippi at Mr. Charles' evidence.","start":1896.998,"stop":1905.236,"duration":8.24},{"text":"That statement, if the Court please, was unwarranted and untrue.","start":1905.236,"stop":1915.736,"duration":10.5},{"text":"I would be less than frank and honest with this Court if I did not say, and I'm not at all proud of it that in the past, Mississippi has been grossly discriminate or discriminatory particularly in the field of registering and voting rights for Negroes, and I say I'm not proud of it.","start":1915.736,"stop":1948.304,"duration":32.57},{"text":"But I can say to this Court that within the past or for the past two years at least, we've done a lot to get our house in order and we need and I think now deserve all the help we can get.","start":1948.304,"stop":1974.323,"duration":26.02},{"text":"I've been an Assistant Attorney General of Mississippi since June of '62 and for the last three years, I've been more or less the liaison between the Attorney General's office, the Governor's Office, and the Department of Justice.","start":1974.323,"stop":1991.017,"duration":16.69},{"text":"Since the fall of 1965, there has been no problem whatsoever in Negroes registering and voting in Mississippi, none whatsoever.","start":1991.017,"stop":2004.79,"duration":13.77},{"text":"Over 200,000 of them are registered there to date.","start":2004.79,"stop":2010.972,"duration":6.18},{"text":"In last summer's general primary -- I mean primary and general elections, more than 75 Negroes were candidates for public office.","start":2010.972,"stop":2020.197,"duration":9.22},{"text":"Between 25 and 30 of them were elected, elected to members of board to supervisors, justices of the peace, constable, clerks to the chancery court, members of school boards, one elected to the legislature.","start":2020.197,"stop":2039.358,"duration":19.16},{"text":"Just last month in a special election to fill the unexpired term of Governor Williams as congressman, there were certain candidates.","start":2039.358,"stop":2048.483,"duration":9.13},{"text":"Candidates in the race, one was Charles Edwards, a Negro.","start":2048.483,"stop":2051.85,"duration":3.37},{"text":"He led the ticket and he's in the runoff in the second primary for the next Tuesday.","start":2051.85,"stop":2061.121,"duration":9.27},{"text":"I know what the situation is there with reference to voting and registering, and there is no problem.","start":2061.121,"stop":2067.518,"duration":6.4},{"text":"In all of the elections last summer, and I worked -- I have pushed all knowledge of this.","start":2067.518,"stop":2072.745,"duration":5.23},{"text":"I worked with the Justice Department.","start":2072.745,"stop":2074.911,"duration":2.17},{"text":"Those elections were observed by federal observers, members of the Justice Department and there was no criticism of any of them, no charges of unfairness in any of them.","start":2074.911,"stop":2086.547,"duration":11.64},{"text":"So I say we've gone a long ways to get our house in order and we need all the help and encouragement we can get.","start":2086.547,"stop":2097.952,"duration":11.41},{"text":"Now, to put this case in perspective, if the Court would please, and I don't know whether Mr. Kinoy sought to confuse everybody but he certainly did me about some of the issues in this matter.","start":2097.952,"stop":2111.55,"duration":13.6},{"text":"In the first place, there is no concession by the State of Mississippi whatsoever that can be found anywhere of selective enforcement of the statute.","start":2111.55,"stop":2127.125,"duration":15.57},{"text":"Here's what counsel is overlooking. Parades on the public streets of Hattiesburg are under the jurisdiction of the Mayor and Commissioners and Police Department of the City of Hattiesburg.","start":2127.125,"stop":2144.809,"duration":17.68},{"text":"The State of Mississippi has no control over those public streets.","start":2144.809,"stop":2149.379,"duration":4.57},{"text":"They are streets that belong to the city, maintained and paved by the city.","start":2149.379,"stop":2154.497,"duration":5.12},{"text":"The sheriff has no supervision over who can use them and who can't.","start":2154.497,"stop":2161.283,"duration":6.79},{"text":"The City has nothing to do with the enforcement of this statute.","start":2161.283,"stop":2167.305,"duration":6.02},{"text":"This statute has to do with protecting publicly owned buildings such as in this instance, courthouses, which are under the jurisdiction of state authorities or county authorities.","start":2167.305,"stop":2183.93,"duration":16.63},{"text":"We are talking about --","start":2183.93,"stop":2184.819,"duration":0.89}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there a parade ordinance in Hattiesburg?","start":2184.819,"stop":2187.276,"duration":2.46}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":2187.276,"stop":2187.723,"duration":0.45},{"text":"There's no parade ordinance in Hattiesburg that I know of at all, but the Court has -- the sheriff would have nothing in the world to do with it.","start":2187.723,"stop":2196.4,"duration":8.68},{"text":"They go to parade there in the public streets, Mr. Justice Stewart, and they are not on the courthouse grounds.","start":2196.4,"stop":2203.21,"duration":6.81},{"text":"They are not on the sidewalks adjoining the courthouse.","start":2203.21,"stop":2206.482,"duration":3.27},{"text":"They are on a public street that just happens to run in front of the courthouse.","start":2206.482,"stop":2210.981,"duration":4.5},{"text":"That --","start":2210.981,"stop":2211.53,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Can anyone parade at anytime he wants, sir?","start":2211.53,"stop":2214.492,"duration":2.96}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"I think, if the Court please, that they make some arrangement with the city for the purpose of the police helping direct traffic and so forth and let them know it, and I know of no problem in the parades.","start":2214.492,"stop":2227.8,"duration":13.31},{"text":"They have school band parades for the schools and if these people want to parade, they could parade.","start":2227.8,"stop":2234.111,"duration":6.31},{"text":"But they go to the city.","start":2234.111,"stop":2235.152,"duration":1.04},{"text":"It got nothing to do with the courthouse.","start":2235.152,"stop":2236.591,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"But if civil rights workers want to parade through the streets and have signs such as they had in this situation, are they free to do it?","start":2236.591,"stop":2246.835,"duration":10.24}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes!","start":2246.835,"stop":2247.219,"duration":0.38},{"text":"There would be absolutely no problem with that as far as the city is concerned.","start":2247.219,"stop":2251.082,"duration":3.86}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"The authorities wouldn't interfere in any way?","start":2251.082,"stop":2252.992,"duration":1.91}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":2252.992,"stop":2254.166,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Any time of the day?","start":2254.166,"stop":2255.251,"duration":1.09}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":2255.251,"stop":2257.784,"duration":2.53},{"text":"We're dealing with a situation --","start":2257.784,"stop":2259.081,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that -- is any of this in the record?","start":2259.081,"stop":2261.674,"duration":2.59}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"Not in the record if the Court please.","start":2261.674,"stop":2262.955,"duration":1.28},{"text":"That didn't come up because it's not a part of it but I happen to know that is the situation.","start":2262.955,"stop":2271.631,"duration":8.68}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, you are rather objecting to Mr. Smith's speaking of the record.","start":2271.631,"stop":2276.056,"duration":4.43},{"text":"I was just wondering if all of this you've told us is in the record.","start":2276.056,"stop":2280.033,"duration":3.98}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":2280.033,"stop":2280.495,"duration":0.46},{"text":"And whether it was an answer to Your Honor's question.","start":2280.495,"stop":2283.212,"duration":2.72}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"No, before.","start":2283.212,"stop":2283.832,"duration":0.62},{"text":"I mean what you were saying before about the conditions and --","start":2283.832,"stop":2287.663,"duration":3.83}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"I was not objecting to -- I was going over --","start":2287.663,"stop":2290.248,"duration":2.59}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- how they are free to parade and so forth at any place.","start":2290.248,"stop":2299.406,"duration":9.16}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"That is not in the record.","start":2299.406,"stop":2300.318,"duration":0.91},{"text":"I was -- I was responding when you asked the question, Mr. Chief Justice.","start":2300.318,"stop":2304.419,"duration":4.1},{"text":"But let's go back if the Court please and get the history of this lawsuit and put it in perspective.","start":2304.419,"stop":2311.199,"duration":6.78},{"text":"Several days prior to January 22nd, and this is all in record, 22nd 1964, leaflets were distributed all throughout Hattiesburg by the COFO Organization, Council of Federate Organizations which was then at that time, calling on Negroes and sympathizers to meet at the courthouse on the 22nd and called it Freedom Day, recommending that the parents take their children out of school and come to the courthouse and about 200 of them assembled and they marched all up and around the courthouse.","start":2311.199,"stop":2347.762,"duration":36.56},{"text":"They were not bothered, they were not molested.","start":2347.762,"stop":2350.525,"duration":2.76},{"text":"The authorities did what they did to keep down any instance and were able to do it.","start":2350.525,"stop":2356.009,"duration":5.48},{"text":"And then from January 22nd on until April 10th, practically every weekday, there was picketing sometimes in small groups, sometimes in larger around the courthouse.","start":2356.009,"stop":2374.172,"duration":18.16}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there any evidence that -- of anybody who was blocked from ingress or regress who could not go in to the courthouse or who could not come out of it without being interfered with?","start":2374.172,"stop":2388.507,"duration":14.34}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"After this statute was passed?","start":2388.507,"stop":2390.436,"duration":1.93}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"At any time.","start":2390.436,"stop":2391.153,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2391.153,"stop":2391.389,"duration":0.24},{"text":"On the day of the arrest, there's evidence here of an attempt of the demonstration agent to come out of the hall.","start":2391.389,"stop":2399.036,"duration":7.65},{"text":"She had to come out to use that and she couldn't.","start":2399.036,"stop":2401.61,"duration":2.57},{"text":"She had to actually fall in to the picket line and march with the picket line all to get out -- get around --","start":2401.61,"stop":2406.689,"duration":5.08}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"I remember that testimony and perhaps one may regard it as impressive or not impressive.","start":2406.689,"stop":2413.212,"duration":6.52},{"text":"I also remember -- seem to remember that it said that that is the only evidence in the record.","start":2413.212,"stop":2418.863,"duration":5.65}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"If the Court would please, we get --","start":2418.863,"stop":2419.5,"duration":0.64}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that so?","start":2419.5,"stop":2420.975,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"That's the only evidence of any particular person, yes sir.","start":2420.975,"stop":2424.201,"duration":3.23},{"text":"But we did not take the position in the trial of this case that we were obligated before the Court on the question of proving that these people were guilty or innocent trying out the facts of whether or not they were guilty of a violation of a statute.","start":2424.201,"stop":2443.506,"duration":19.3},{"text":"That's a matter to be tried before a jury as each one of them I don't know.","start":2443.506,"stop":2448.049,"duration":4.54},{"text":"They would have to be judged from separate affidavits, be proven beyond -- guilty beyond reasonable doubt.","start":2448.049,"stop":2454.963,"duration":6.91},{"text":"They're entitled to a jury trial and we did not take it that that Court of Equity was there to try the facts as to whether each individual was guilty or not but the question of whether or not that this was a good faith prosecution and not something to harass.","start":2454.963,"stop":2473.075,"duration":18.11},{"text":"Now, coming on back to the parade or to the demonstration, as Mr. Dukes testified, this was on tax collecting time and this was being done in such a way that people just couldn't even get in to the front of the courthouse to pay the taxes, so the city and the county guard --","start":2473.075,"stop":2487.363,"duration":14.29}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's what I was asking.","start":2487.363,"stop":2488.469,"duration":1.11},{"text":"Is anything like that in the record?","start":2488.469,"stop":2491.96,"duration":3.49}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"That was Mr. Dukes' testimony that that was a situation at the beginning back in --","start":2491.96,"stop":2495.731,"duration":3.77}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"That people could not get in to the front of the courthouse.","start":2495.731,"stop":2498.424,"duration":2.69}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2498.424,"stop":2500.094,"duration":1.67},{"text":"You said that they were blocking the front entrances of this courthouse.","start":2500.094,"stop":2502.975,"duration":2.88}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"There is testimony to that effect?","start":2502.975,"stop":2504.309,"duration":1.33}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2504.309,"stop":2504.798,"duration":0.49},{"text":"In this opinion.","start":2504.798,"stop":2505.66,"duration":0.86}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Where is it?","start":2505.66,"stop":2506.521,"duration":0.86},{"text":"Where do we find it?","start":2506.521,"stop":2508.126,"duration":1.61}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"As to the matter, if the Court please, I suggest that you will find on page 245 and 246 of the appendix and Mr. Dukes, the county attorney's testimony on 246.","start":2508.126,"stop":2571.436,"duration":63.31},{"text":"I asked him this question, “Well, after these big marches and his great group, was there any effort made to set up some barricades and outline a place where they could picket?”","start":2571.436,"stop":2579.493,"duration":8.06},{"text":"“It was absolutely necessary, Mr. Wells because the manner in which they are raising to picket completely blocked the front entrance of the courthouse.","start":2579.493,"stop":2587.567,"duration":8.07},{"text":"And being in January and the tax paying time, we had to make some arrangements for our people to get to the courthouse or barricades were set up on north and south of the main street and so forth, and asked them to picket there.”","start":2587.567,"stop":2599.843,"duration":12.28}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"And after -- but after the barricades were set up and at the time of the arrest, there's no such testimony, is there?","start":2599.843,"stop":2606.76,"duration":6.92}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"Then after the barricades were set up and they were asked to picket in this one area, Mr. Justice Fortas, there is no testimony other than some testimony stating that during that time, Mr. Dukes testified that --","start":2606.76,"stop":2635.077,"duration":28.32}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Where -- where is this testimony?","start":2635.077,"stop":2638.978,"duration":3.9},{"text":"Can you find this testimony of the Court?","start":2638.978,"stop":2673.781,"duration":34.8}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"The question asked Mr. Dukes by Judge Rives, I believe, just a minute please.","start":2673.781,"stop":2756.035,"duration":82.25},{"text":"On page 267 of appendix, Mr. Chief Justice, Judge Rives says, “Mr. Dukes, may I ask you, did any persons complain to you as a prosecuting officer, the county prosecuting attorney of the county that they had undertaken to gain access to the courthouse and access have been brought by the witness?”","start":2756.035,"stop":2776.614,"duration":20.58},{"text":"“Judge Rives, we had complaints since January 21st constantly.”","start":2776.614,"stop":2781.544,"duration":4.93}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, is that a part of the evidentiary record?","start":2781.544,"stop":2784.351,"duration":2.81}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2784.351,"stop":2784.671,"duration":0.32},{"text":"This is in the appendix.","start":2784.671,"stop":2787.044,"duration":2.37},{"text":"Page 267, it is part of the -- the transcript of the testimony of the full three-judge court.","start":2787.044,"stop":2794.287,"duration":7.24}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"I wonder if this question and answer isn't more column heading.","start":2794.287,"stop":2801.893,"duration":7.61},{"text":"On page 246, I guess it's Mr. Dukes who is testifying and Mr. Wells was asking a question yourself.","start":2801.893,"stop":2812.288,"duration":10.39}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2812.288,"stop":2813.807,"duration":1.52}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"“Now, starting about around April 1st, Mr. Dukes, I believe they were picketing their free will everyday.”","start":2813.807,"stop":2822.975,"duration":9.17},{"text":"Answer, “I believe that's correct.”","start":2822.975,"stop":2826.41,"duration":3.43},{"text":"“Were they in any great large numbers at that time?”","start":2826.41,"stop":2830.26,"duration":3.85},{"text":"Answer, “It would vary, Mr. Wells.","start":2830.26,"stop":2833.794,"duration":3.53},{"text":"They were not in these large numbers, of course.","start":2833.794,"stop":2837.042,"duration":3.25},{"text":"This came on January 22nd, which was several hundred.","start":2837.042,"stop":2842.021,"duration":4.98},{"text":"But it would vary anywhere from 7, 8, 13, 14, 15, and so forth, some grown, some young.”","start":2842.021,"stop":2854.944,"duration":12.92},{"text":"Now, is that the -- was that the extent of the picketing after -- after the police blocked off the way, 6 or 7 or 8 or up to 13, 14, 15, some young and some --","start":2854.944,"stop":2872.396,"duration":17.45}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":2872.396,"stop":2872.942,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- someone else.","start":2872.942,"stop":2874.446,"duration":1.5}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"That was the extent right on -- up until.","start":2874.446,"stop":2878.021,"duration":3.58}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, while that was being done in that -- in that degree, was there any effort on the part of these people to block anyone from the entry or exit from the courthouse, or was there anything done by them that had that effect?","start":2878.021,"stop":2894.198,"duration":16.18}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":2894.198,"stop":2895.666,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"So the last two months or so, there was no interference of any kind with anybody going into that courthouse.","start":2895.666,"stop":2903.719,"duration":8.05}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"At those small numbers, not as far as the record is concerned and we knew.","start":2903.719,"stop":2906.831,"duration":3.11},{"text":"No, sir.","start":2906.831,"stop":2907.478,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's what we're dealing with --","start":2907.478,"stop":2908.629,"duration":1.15}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":2908.629,"stop":2909.414,"duration":0.79},{"text":"Now, if the Court would please, following that.","start":2909.414,"stop":2912.379,"duration":2.96}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"I beg your pardon?","start":2912.379,"stop":2913.059,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"Now following this in April when this statute was passed, and it wasn't passed just for Hattiesburg.","start":2913.059,"stop":2920.738,"duration":7.68},{"text":"We had the situation in various parts of the state.","start":2920.738,"stop":2923.581,"duration":2.84},{"text":"When this statute was passed, it became the law.","start":2923.581,"stop":2931.194,"duration":7.61},{"text":"On the 9th of April, the county attorney, the district attorney, the sheriff and his deputies came out about four o'clock and the sheriff asked these people to stop -- I want to read you something, is that the state of Mississippi has passed this statute and I want you to hear it read.","start":2931.194,"stop":2957.978,"duration":26.78},{"text":"And they read the statute to them in detail and he said, “Now, I do not want to have to arrest you people but you cannot picket in such ways as to obstruct or interfere with the entrances and exits of this courthouse.”","start":2957.978,"stop":2974.955,"duration":16.98}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"How many people were there at that time?","start":2974.955,"stop":2978.112,"duration":3.16}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"At that time, the record is not clear but there were some 15 or 20, Mr. Justice Marshall.","start":2978.112,"stop":2984.133,"duration":6.02}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there anything in the record that they were obstructing?","start":2984.133,"stop":2988.308,"duration":4.18}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"On that occasion?","start":2988.308,"stop":2990.196,"duration":1.89}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2990.196,"stop":2990.659,"duration":0.46}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":2990.659,"stop":2991.201,"duration":0.54},{"text":"There's nothing in the record that --","start":2991.201,"stop":2991.95,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Then what was the necessity of reading the statute to them?","start":2991.95,"stop":2995.846,"duration":3.9}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"He wanted to advice them that as he explained to them, the way at times you have been doing it, you have been blocking these entrances and I want you to know it and ask you to -- I'm not saying you can't picket but do it in such a way and space yourself in such a way as you won't do it.","start":2995.846,"stop":3018.115,"duration":22.27}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Did he tell them that?","start":3018.115,"stop":3019.014,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":3019.014,"stop":3019.616,"duration":0.6},{"text":"The record shows that he told them.","start":3019.616,"stop":3021.265,"duration":1.65}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"And then, how many --","start":3021.265,"stop":3022.585,"duration":1.32}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"Now that night, Mr. Justice Marshall, that night they had a meeting.","start":3022.585,"stop":3031.139,"duration":8.55},{"text":"They discussed the statute with a lawyer.","start":3031.139,"stop":3037.652,"duration":6.51},{"text":"They came to the conclusion that it was unconstitutional.","start":3037.652,"stop":3041.888,"duration":4.24},{"text":"They prepared the written statement for the press and the next morning, they came not in these numbers but some 40 of them came.","start":3041.888,"stop":3056.094,"duration":14.21}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Did they obstruct any entrances?","start":3056.094,"stop":3057.966,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":3057.966,"stop":3059.434,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Where is that in the record?","start":3059.434,"stop":3060.108,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Where is that in the record?","start":3060.108,"stop":3062.543,"duration":2.43}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"This one later that tried to get out and then the sheriff and the county attorney himself went out and tried to see if they could move against it and the pictures themselves, if the Court please, in here show it became -- it could be a picket line and became a picket fence and it shows right at their entrances that they were --","start":3062.543,"stop":3083.735,"duration":21.19}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"What is the testimony on it?","start":3083.735,"stop":3085.571,"duration":1.84}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"The testimony from Mrs. -- testimony of Mrs. Bricket beginning on page 268 of the appendix.","start":3085.571,"stop":3152.439,"duration":66.87},{"text":"Now, on the bottom of page 269, “Now, Mrs. Bricket, in connection with the duties of your since she was home demonstration aid, do you frequently have occasion to go to the can agent so?”","start":3152.439,"stop":3173.225,"duration":20.79},{"text":"“Yes, sir.”","start":3173.225,"stop":3173.864,"duration":0.64},{"text":"“Generally by how?”","start":3173.864,"stop":3174.676,"duration":0.81},{"text":"“Sometimes four, five times a day.","start":3174.676,"stop":3176.625,"duration":1.95},{"text":"It varies from day to day.”","start":3176.625,"stop":3179.636,"duration":3.01},{"text":"And she goes on and explains her situation and the condition that existed there, that day.","start":3179.636,"stop":3183.852,"duration":4.22},{"text":"She testified that there were some 35 or 40 who were walking there very close together.","start":3183.852,"stop":3191.06,"duration":7.21},{"text":"“Did you have on occasion, during the time that that line was being picketed, to go to the courthouse?”","start":3191.06,"stop":3195.108,"duration":4.05},{"text":"“Yes, sir.","start":3195.108,"stop":3195.517,"duration":0.41},{"text":"To pick up some materials.”","start":3195.517,"stop":3197.122,"duration":1.61},{"text":"“Would you tell the court just what happened and how you got there?”","start":3197.122,"stop":3200.062,"duration":2.94},{"text":"“I started the regular route and they were so close together that I had to wait for just a moment to get in line and I fell in line with them and started weaving back and forth until I reached until the front steps and then dropped out of the line and got in the courthouse.”","start":3200.062,"stop":3213.848,"duration":13.79}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"How long would you say the walkway was, were prescribed by the authorities for these people to walk around?","start":3213.848,"stop":3224.844,"duration":11}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"From beginning of -- start all the way around -- if the Court would please, they would walk -- as this picture shows, part of this walkway was in the courthouse ground.","start":3224.844,"stop":3234.867,"duration":10.02}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Where are the pictures?","start":3234.867,"stop":3237.284,"duration":2.42}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"The pictures are in the appendix.","start":3237.284,"stop":3242.45,"duration":5.17},{"text":"All these exhibits are in the appendix, Mr. Justice Black, beginning at page -- on page 93 of the -- well, just a minute.","start":3242.45,"stop":3251.843,"duration":9.39},{"text":"The pictures -- 95 of the appendix and run through 102.","start":3251.843,"stop":3268.026,"duration":16.18}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, perhaps you can help me on this.","start":3268.026,"stop":3269.704,"duration":1.68},{"text":"I find -- I may misunderstand this but I find Mrs. Bricket's testimony very unimpressive that I get the picture correctly or maybe I don't.","start":3269.704,"stop":3280.449,"duration":10.74},{"text":"She said she came out of her office and she had to go on a walk, which was why it's enough for only person at the walk so that you couldn't have two people walking abreast.","start":3280.449,"stop":3292.708,"duration":12.26},{"text":"And there was a picket line there and in order to get to where she was going, she had to fall in line -- fall in behind some of the pickets.","start":3292.708,"stop":3302.989,"duration":10.28},{"text":"Am I wrong about that picture so I read it on 270?","start":3302.989,"stop":3307.8,"duration":4.81}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"If I can illustrate this by these pictures, which she was --","start":3307.8,"stop":3317.012,"duration":9.21}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that would get to the --","start":3317.012,"stop":3322.708,"duration":5.7}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"If the Court would please, this sketch at page 86 -- let's see, there's one on 86, see if I've got --","start":3322.708,"stop":3333.628,"duration":10.92}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's at 71.","start":3333.628,"stop":3337.156,"duration":3.53}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"71.","start":3337.156,"stop":3347.15,"duration":9.99},{"text":"If the Court please, the way that drawing came about is this way.","start":3347.15,"stop":3354.374,"duration":7.22},{"text":"After this hearing involuntary, Judge Rives who was there with his law clerk and his law clerk's wife decided to go back to Montgomery by way of Hattiesburg, and he went by and made an inspection of the situation as existed then, which was some good long private practice the same.","start":3354.374,"stop":3384.167,"duration":29.79},{"text":"And I understand he's -- and this -- I got this information alone.","start":3384.167,"stop":3388.443,"duration":4.28},{"text":"I got from him, so he's not --","start":3388.443,"stop":3390.021,"duration":1.58}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, let's take what's in the records, if you please.","start":3390.021,"stop":3392.95,"duration":2.93}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, I have -- I think how this got into the record.","start":3392.95,"stop":3396.417,"duration":3.47},{"text":"This was prepared by Judge Rives himself personally on his law clerk --","start":3396.417,"stop":3400.592,"duration":4.18}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But that's not my question, whether it would help us understand where this lady was, where the walk is so to help us understand what the layout was.","start":3400.592,"stop":3414.202,"duration":13.61}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":3414.202,"stop":3415.167,"duration":0.96}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I mean the -- the several entrances --","start":3415.167,"stop":3420.038,"duration":4.87}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"Alright sir, the line of march, Mr. Justice Brennan, to the lower part of this drawing and to the left is the sidewalk on the public street coming on around to Eaton Street.","start":3420.038,"stop":3445.194,"duration":25.16},{"text":"Then, you'll notice this little -- as he's got it .31 walk at least from the street running north, runs on up by here.","start":3445.194,"stop":3453.824,"duration":8.63},{"text":"It curves a little bit to the left, the line march, it comes back out, and that's the circle they were making.","start":3453.824,"stop":3458.771,"duration":4.95}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, at that point, it says 3.8.","start":3458.771,"stop":3461.342,"duration":2.57},{"text":"Is that a building?","start":3461.342,"stop":3463.803,"duration":2.46},{"text":"I notice north of the line --","start":3463.803,"stop":3468.519,"duration":4.72}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"3.8?","start":3468.519,"stop":3469.526,"duration":1.01}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, that's the width of the walk.","start":3469.526,"stop":3471.394,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"That's the width of the walk.","start":3471.394,"stop":3472.969,"duration":1.58}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"So what -- I forgot to say it in.","start":3472.969,"stop":3476.039,"duration":3.07},{"text":"What building was she leaving?","start":3476.039,"stop":3477.256,"duration":1.22}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"Mrs. Bricket's office -- the courthouse is here to the right of this drawing.","start":3477.256,"stop":3483.406,"duration":6.15}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3483.406,"stop":3483.769,"duration":0.36}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"In other words, this is a courthouse steps right here, in front of them.","start":3483.769,"stop":3486.955,"duration":3.19},{"text":"And this is the courthouse --","start":3486.955,"stop":3488.413,"duration":1.46}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And what's the entrance she was leaving?","start":3488.413,"stop":3490.124,"duration":1.71},{"text":"That's all.","start":3490.124,"stop":3490.548,"duration":0.42}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"She was leaving -- her office is where this entrance to Home Demonstration Office here you see there, that's her office.","start":3490.548,"stop":3499.496,"duration":8.95}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And she was coming out of that --","start":3499.496,"stop":3500.589,"duration":1.09}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"She comes out of there and comes around to her right as she comes out --","start":3500.589,"stop":3505.182,"duration":4.59}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And that is where it says 6.7 --","start":3505.182,"stop":3506.857,"duration":1.68}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":3506.857,"stop":3507.214,"duration":0.36},{"text":"And then comes out into this area and follows this line in here to go up into the courthouse.","start":3507.214,"stop":3513.132,"duration":5.92}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Where was the picket line?","start":3513.132,"stop":3514.435,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"The picket line was right across here.","start":3514.435,"stop":3515.926,"duration":1.49},{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":3515.926,"stop":3516.741,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Has she stepped into the line --","start":3516.741,"stop":3518.299,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"She had to come in, couldn't get through.","start":3518.299,"stop":3520.765,"duration":2.47},{"text":"She had to step in the line and weave her way until she could get out.","start":3520.765,"stop":3524.503,"duration":3.74}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Walked right along that walk 6.7 feet wide?","start":3524.503,"stop":3527.921,"duration":3.42}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":3527.921,"stop":3528.615,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The line where the march passed that's a point where it says 3.8 --","start":3528.615,"stop":3532.872,"duration":4.26}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":3532.872,"stop":3533.103,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and she stepped into the line?","start":3533.103,"stop":3534.404,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":3534.404,"stop":3535.282,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I gather that's only wide enough for one person at 3.8.","start":3535.282,"stop":3540.568,"duration":5.29}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"Just about.","start":3540.568,"stop":3541.884,"duration":1.32}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yeah.","start":3541.884,"stop":3542.836,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I want you to understand the issues basically for --","start":3542.836,"stop":3550.34,"duration":7.5}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice Harlan, here's where -- what I see the issue to be in this case, is our position that this statute is about as narrowly drawn as it could be.","start":3550.34,"stop":3566.01,"duration":15.67}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Which one, the last one?","start":3566.01,"stop":3567.648,"duration":1.64}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, both of them or the last one and the way this came about as there is one that statute was first passed, the word “unreasonable” was not in there preceding the word “interfere”.","start":3567.648,"stop":3580.527,"duration":12.88},{"text":"It was to obstruct or interfere.","start":3580.527,"stop":3583.596,"duration":3.07},{"text":"To be quite frank, it was my thinking that even at court where you talk about interfering, any little thing can be interfering and I felt and I still feel and it was at my suggestion that the legislature amended that statute and to put the word “unreasonable” before interfere because it would be my opinion that any court would interpret it to be an unreasonable interference rather than just some little interference.","start":3583.596,"stop":3609.137,"duration":25.54},{"text":"I think unreasonable interference narrows it rather than broadens it and it was actually at my suggestion to legislature did that.","start":3609.137,"stop":3618.234,"duration":9.1}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I could just wish you could do that to deal with one square 2283 did this junction.","start":3618.234,"stop":3624.606,"duration":6.37}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":3624.606,"stop":3625.628,"duration":1.02}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And if it doesn't or if it does that whether or not on the Dombrowski federal court notwithstanding as a jurisdictional injunction, either on the theory of the vagueness of the statute on its face or because there's evidence in the record (Inaudible) for enforcement of the statute.","start":3625.628,"stop":3650.462,"duration":24.83}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"That's just exactly if the Court please --","start":3650.462,"stop":3652.198,"duration":1.74}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Maybe we can spend all the time and the lower courts can spend all the time trying the issue of guilt or innocence in Federal Court of Equity to determine whether or not any of those legal questions are to justifies on each of this injunction.","start":3652.198,"stop":3667.205,"duration":15.01}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3667.205,"stop":3667.805,"duration":0.6},{"text":"Now, Mr. Justice Harlan, let me --","start":3667.805,"stop":3669.006,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Before we get to that, is there -- isn't there also the question as to whether -- whether these people did demonstrate in such a manner as to obstruct or interfere with free ingress or egress to or from any public premises?","start":3669.006,"stop":3688.038,"duration":19.03},{"text":"Now, isn't -- isn't that an issue in the case?","start":3688.038,"stop":3690.447,"duration":2.41}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"If the Court please, the factual issue as to whether anyone of them did, I don't think it's for Court of Equity to determine.","start":3690.447,"stop":3700.292,"duration":9.84},{"text":"I think that the question -- the view to determine here is this, is this a good faith, honest good faith prosecution that's not just done to harass somebody?","start":3700.292,"stop":3710.636,"duration":10.34},{"text":"Can they get a fair trial in the courts of Mississippi?","start":3710.636,"stop":3714.23,"duration":3.59}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, but you -- you have put in this record all of these diagrams and you put all these pictures in here for the purpose of showing that there was an unreasonable demonstration.","start":3714.23,"stop":3728.066,"duration":13.84},{"text":"Now, isn't it an issue in this case whether -- whether they did obstruct or in such a manner the ingress or egress tour from -- do you want us to forget about those now?","start":3728.066,"stop":3739.56,"duration":11.49}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"But these pictures were put in there for this purpose, to show that at least they have probable cause here to justify some judge.","start":3739.56,"stop":3753.601,"duration":14.04},{"text":"Now --","start":3753.601,"stop":3754.031,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You take the position as I understand it the natural and normal way to try to defend it in this country is where he is in a court charged with the offense and can get a trial by jury that he is entitled to.","start":3754.031,"stop":3767.369,"duration":13.34}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":3767.369,"stop":3768.286,"duration":0.92}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And that you -- we are not here to pass on that question at this time after the guilt or innocence of either one of them.","start":3768.286,"stop":3775.203,"duration":6.92}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"That's exactly my position, if the Court would please.","start":3775.203,"stop":3776.974,"duration":1.77},{"text":"That's exactly the position I took with the lower court and as Judge Coleman said, we are not trying to try these people as to whether they are guilty --","start":3776.974,"stop":3782.37,"duration":5.4}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Can I ask you another question?","start":3782.37,"stop":3783.804,"duration":1.43}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":3783.804,"stop":3784.158,"duration":0.35}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"How do you know that there's an alleged offense committed?","start":3784.158,"stop":3788.304,"duration":4.15}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"The alleged offense was committed, Mr. Justice Harlan, on April 10, 1964.","start":3788.304,"stop":3801.512,"duration":13.21}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And what are the tradition of your state court in Mississippi with respect to the trial of this case whether you've taken four years to have this case to approve the state courts and then to come up here?","start":3801.512,"stop":3814.791,"duration":13.28}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"If the Court please, this cases could be tried in -- that in the county court, they could be tried in short order.","start":3814.791,"stop":3829.275,"duration":14.48},{"text":"I mean that I do not grant at all.","start":3829.275,"stop":3833.098,"duration":3.82},{"text":"They then could be appealed to the Circuit Court on the record, that's made there and then the Supreme Court of Mississippi and then here.","start":3833.098,"stop":3841.703,"duration":8.61}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"How long would it take between the trial court and the Circuit Court?","start":3841.703,"stop":3848.981,"duration":7.28}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"I'll say probably 60 days.","start":3848.981,"stop":3853.173,"duration":4.19}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"And how long would it -- would it take the Supreme Court of Mississippi to decide this case normally?","start":3853.173,"stop":3859.947,"duration":6.77},{"text":"Now, I'm -- I'm talking about this kind of cases normally.","start":3859.947,"stop":3865.237,"duration":5.29}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"If court is up with its docket for the full, Mr. Chief Justice, I would say four months outside.","start":3865.237,"stop":3873.693,"duration":8.46}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Four months outside, four months from the time of --","start":3873.693,"stop":3876.358,"duration":2.66}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"From the Circuit Court to Supreme Court, yes sir.","start":3876.358,"stop":3880.041,"duration":3.68}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there a law in Mississippi that forbids the defendants to raise the constitutionality of this statute?","start":3880.041,"stop":3885.812,"duration":5.77}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"They have actually raised it in this case, in its inception before they were removed.","start":3885.812,"stop":3890.665,"duration":4.85}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"In Mississippi courts?","start":3890.665,"stop":3891.763,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3891.763,"stop":3894.816,"duration":3.05}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Now we've been four years -- four years decided whether or not the federal courts have the right to enjoin the prosecution.","start":3894.816,"stop":3906.447,"duration":11.63}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"And --","start":3906.447,"stop":3907.091,"duration":0.64}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And in the meantime, the state prosecution will handle the state's stay.","start":3907.091,"stop":3911.75,"duration":4.66}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":3911.75,"stop":3914.139,"duration":2.39},{"text":"And may I say even this, Mr. Justice Harlan, that even if you would determine whether you had the right to do it, it's the question of whether they're entitled any relief in the criteria of Dombrowski in this case.","start":3914.139,"stop":3932.219,"duration":18.08},{"text":"The theory on which they ask for these injunctions to start with was this, and they admitted though for us that the purpose of these demonstrations was voting registration.","start":3932.219,"stop":3942.398,"duration":10.18},{"text":"And in their motion for preliminary injunction all the way through, that unless they were enjoined, there would discourage Negroes from registering to vote and correct they're moot.","start":3942.398,"stop":3956.393,"duration":13.99},{"text":"The facts in this record show that after the last arrests were made, the ones that they say that if you stop us from doing this it's going to cut down the registration, the record shows that from the time of the arrest and when there's picketing as much as was seized that more Negroes registered after that until the time of this trial than had registered prior to it.","start":3956.393,"stop":3986.971,"duration":30.58}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Does the record also show the part that federal government had in that?","start":3986.971,"stop":3992.577,"duration":5.61}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"This -- there was one witness who testified in connection with suit against Mr. Lien, yes sir, the registrar.","start":3992.577,"stop":4008.43,"duration":15.85}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"We don't know whether this helped or hurt, do we?","start":4008.43,"stop":4013.089,"duration":4.66}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"As far as the record is concerned, Mr. Justice Marshall, the record has put in strong that it did not hurt.","start":4013.089,"stop":4020.962,"duration":7.87}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, did the record show that they continued to picket?","start":4020.962,"stop":4024.99,"duration":4.03}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"After these arrests on April 10th and 11th, they continued to picket there in smaller numbers not blocking the entrance for 38 days.","start":4024.99,"stop":4038.858,"duration":13.87}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"And there wasn't an arrest?","start":4038.858,"stop":4040.417,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"And there was no arrest.","start":4040.417,"stop":4041.971,"duration":1.55}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"What about Mr. Kinoy said some seven people were arrested?","start":4041.971,"stop":4045.139,"duration":3.17}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"In just a minute, I'll come to that if I may.","start":4045.139,"stop":4048.241,"duration":3.1},{"text":"Here's what happened.","start":4048.241,"stop":4049.055,"duration":0.81},{"text":"On the 10th that morning, these 38 or 40 people were arrested.","start":4049.055,"stop":4057.363,"duration":8.31},{"text":"That afternoon, there were nine more arrested.","start":4057.363,"stop":4063.818,"duration":6.46}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"For doing what?","start":4063.818,"stop":4064.782,"duration":0.96}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"They were there --","start":4064.782,"stop":4065.696,"duration":0.91}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Obstructing?","start":4065.696,"stop":4066.795,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"Just a minute now, please sir.","start":4066.795,"stop":4069.34,"duration":2.55},{"text":"As soon as the county attorney found out about the nine arrests that afternoon, all but one were juveniles.","start":4069.34,"stop":4077.439,"duration":8.1},{"text":"They were immediately released to their parents and no charges were made against them and have made on against them.","start":4077.439,"stop":4083.691,"duration":6.25},{"text":"And the one made against the one grown person that was there leading them, if it ever gets back to state court, it's going to be dismissed, so they don't have a problem with adjoining those.","start":4083.691,"stop":4094.006,"duration":10.32}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Why is that going to be dismissed?","start":4094.006,"stop":4096.55,"duration":2.54}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"Because she would be there alone, Mr. Chief Justice.","start":4096.55,"stop":4100.714,"duration":4.16},{"text":"They were with these children.","start":4100.714,"stop":4102.234,"duration":1.52},{"text":"These arrests were made by the deputy sheriff and after checking into it by the county attorney, he felt these were juveniles in the first place and he felt that it would not warrant to go ahead and charge them with it.","start":4102.234,"stop":4114.179,"duration":11.94},{"text":"They were released to their parents and kept in a short time.","start":4114.179,"stop":4120.426,"duration":6.25},{"text":"In other words, Mr. Chief Justice, sometimes an officer can make a mistake in arresting somebody.","start":4120.426,"stop":4127.227,"duration":6.8},{"text":"When somebody finds out, they'll say, “Well, I'm not going to prosecute.”","start":4127.227,"stop":4130.085,"duration":2.86},{"text":"Those things can happen, not necessarily in these areas but in other areas, and he felt it was not enough sufficient evidence to justify a prosecution.","start":4130.085,"stop":4139.622,"duration":9.54}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"How young were they?","start":4139.622,"stop":4140.621,"duration":1},{"text":"As young as one of the little children shown in these pictures --","start":4140.621,"stop":4146.652,"duration":6.03}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":4146.652,"stop":4146.932,"duration":0.28}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that you have?","start":4146.932,"stop":4148.304,"duration":1.37}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"They were --","start":4148.304,"stop":4148.519,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"There -- there's a little child in --","start":4148.519,"stop":4151.785,"duration":3.27}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":4151.785,"stop":4152.154,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- they were align and --","start":4152.154,"stop":4154.286,"duration":2.13}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":4154.286,"stop":4154.649,"duration":0.36},{"text":"They were -- 14, 15, 16, and 17 years old.","start":4154.649,"stop":4157.715,"duration":3.07},{"text":"I beg your pardon?","start":4157.715,"stop":4158.252,"duration":0.54}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I suppose Mississippi is not responsible for having the little child in line.","start":4158.252,"stop":4167.553,"duration":9.3}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":4167.553,"stop":4170.491,"duration":2.94},{"text":"We feel we take this position, if Your Honor would please, this statute is certainly as narrowly drawn as I think it could be and we feel that the state has certainly got a right to go no further than they have.","start":4170.491,"stop":4185.075,"duration":14.58}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask you a question?","start":4185.075,"stop":4186.059,"duration":0.98},{"text":"Are you familiar with ex parte Young?","start":4186.059,"stop":4189.395,"duration":3.34}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"Ex parte --","start":4189.395,"stop":4190.345,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"The case -- our case of ex parte Young where prosecutions were enjoined and this Court sustained them?","start":4190.345,"stop":4199.899,"duration":9.55}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice Black, I have read the case but I frankly am not --","start":4199.899,"stop":4203.343,"duration":3.44}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it showed that unless an injunction was issued, there would be various harassments such as constantly arresting, increasing the fine from day to day so that it might be within a few weeks, a fine of a million dollars would be imposed, and various things like where the state was about to harass these people to death.","start":4203.343,"stop":4230.416,"duration":27.07},{"text":"And under those circumstances, it was still -- and those circumstances will require -- was held that the state could be enjoined from doing it under they could get it tested in way which did not take all their money away from them and send them to jail for life.","start":4230.416,"stop":4248.38,"duration":17.96},{"text":"Has there been any threat like that in Mississippi in these cases?","start":4248.38,"stop":4251.485,"duration":3.1}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":4251.485,"stop":4252.064,"duration":0.58},{"text":"None whatsoever.","start":4252.064,"stop":4255.995,"duration":3.93}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I would take that case is more relevant than Dombrowski.","start":4255.995,"stop":4260.974,"duration":4.98}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"But proof that this thing shows, if Your Honor would please, the very thing happened from April 11th until May 18th, they continued to picket in the same area but in small enough numbers not to block anything and they were not molested.","start":4260.974,"stop":4277.295,"duration":16.32},{"text":"On the 18th of May or the 28th of May -- back in May, another large group came and there were some arrests made there when they came in large numbers again and it blocked.","start":4277.295,"stop":4292.269,"duration":14.97}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that were the seven that Mr. Kinoy spoke about?","start":4292.269,"stop":4296.426,"duration":4.16}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":4296.426,"stop":4296.759,"duration":0.33},{"text":"He's talking about that afternoon on --","start":4296.759,"stop":4298.92,"duration":2.16}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"I beg your pardon?","start":4298.92,"stop":4300.065,"duration":1.14}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":4300.065,"stop":4301.047,"duration":0.98},{"text":"The seven that he was talking about, they actually were nine and not seven, the ones I was talking about by the juveniles.","start":4301.047,"stop":4306.403,"duration":5.36},{"text":"In May --","start":4306.403,"stop":4306.656,"duration":0.25}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"What was that seven he told?","start":4306.656,"stop":4308.262,"duration":1.61}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"In -- in May --","start":4308.262,"stop":4309.77,"duration":1.51}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"I beg your pardon?","start":4309.77,"stop":4310.618,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"In May, there has -- there were some 15 or 20 arrested in May as I recall.","start":4310.618,"stop":4316.872,"duration":6.25}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that on the record?","start":4316.872,"stop":4319.836,"duration":2.96}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"I think Mr. Dukes has testified.","start":4319.836,"stop":4321.546,"duration":1.71},{"text":"He was asked about it.","start":4321.546,"stop":4322.408,"duration":0.86},{"text":"He said he did not remember how many but there was a large group.","start":4322.408,"stop":4325.338,"duration":2.93},{"text":"Mr. Dukes has accounted to it.","start":4325.338,"stop":4330.203,"duration":4.87}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Did they obstruct anybody's ability to enter or leave the courthouse in the following occasions?","start":4330.203,"stop":4338.403,"duration":8.2}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"If the Court please, that I do not know if the record is saying on that.","start":4338.403,"stop":4342.242,"duration":3.84},{"text":"They were -- that's what they were charged with having done in that large group on that day.","start":4342.242,"stop":4354.396,"duration":12.15},{"text":"We feel, if the Court please, that this statute without regard to whether or not 2283 is a law, we feel first that the statute is not unconstitutional on its face.","start":4354.396,"stop":4371.765,"duration":17.37},{"text":"We feel that there's no showing here that it's being constitutionally applied to these people.","start":4371.765,"stop":4381.518,"duration":9.75},{"text":"The -- the argument about the selective enforcement is covered in Judge Coleman's opinion in dealing with parades in the city and the public street on the one hand, that it had nothing to with the sidewalks adjoining the courthouse and walkways going in to the courthouse.","start":4381.518,"stop":4405.993,"duration":24.48},{"text":"They're not synonymous at all because the statute doesn't come into place.","start":4405.993,"stop":4409.568,"duration":3.57},{"text":"Even Judge Rives at some of his questions, he said the Court would be interested in what he would -- what he asked -- Judge Rives asked Mr. Dukes on -- on page 265 of the appendix.","start":4409.568,"stop":4437.413,"duration":27.84},{"text":"And Mr. Dukes, he was the prosecuting attorney.","start":4437.413,"stop":4444.107,"duration":6.69},{"text":"Judge Rives, when there was a colloquy between Mr. Smith and me about the difference between parades and the kind he was talking about in demonstrations.","start":4444.107,"stop":4452.789,"duration":8.68},{"text":"This kind Judge Rives thinks, said, “I think we'd get into an argument on the law.”","start":4452.789,"stop":4457.039,"duration":4.25},{"text":"“I would like to ask the witness however can a plaintiff be granted to parade in such a manner in your opinion as to block the entrance to the courthouse?”","start":4457.039,"stop":4466.041,"duration":9},{"text":"By the witness, “No, sir; I do not think so.”","start":4466.041,"stop":4468.753,"duration":2.71},{"text":"Judge Rives, “In other words, could the city ground appointment to violate that statute?”","start":4468.753,"stop":4474.02,"duration":5.27},{"text":"The witness, “Did the city grant appointment to march around the courtyard to violate statute?","start":4474.02,"stop":4478.895,"duration":4.88},{"text":"No, sir; I don't think so,” Judge Rives, “Permits and the statute are two separate things?”","start":4478.895,"stop":4484.488,"duration":5.59},{"text":"“Yes.”","start":4484.488,"stop":4485.826,"duration":1.34},{"text":"It's definitely my opinion that the city certainly could bring in information to violate the state statute.","start":4485.826,"stop":4491.063,"duration":5.24},{"text":"Then Judge Coleman, “Let me ask you this, the parading that you've been talking about, was that in the streets or was that on the courthouse grounds and adjacent to the entrances to the courthouse?”","start":4491.063,"stop":4496.748,"duration":5.68},{"text":"“It was in the streets, Your Honor.”","start":4496.748,"stop":4499.374,"duration":2.63}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"I was wondering a few moments ago when you said you thought this statute was drawn as tightly as it could be done, I was wondering why it couldn't have said that any -- any group of people who mass with the intention of blocking off the ingress and egress from the -- from the courthouse.","start":4499.374,"stop":4533.13,"duration":33.76},{"text":"I'm wondering why -- that couldn't have been said in there.","start":4533.13,"stop":4536.399,"duration":3.27}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, the statute is not against somebody who gets together with the intention or with a conspiracy or with a purpose.","start":4536.399,"stop":4545.162,"duration":8.76},{"text":"It posed to set down to this, that you actually do it.","start":4545.162,"stop":4551.555,"duration":6.39},{"text":"That you actually do it, that's why this is prohibited.","start":4551.555,"stop":4556.515,"duration":4.96},{"text":"There's no prohibition against picketing.","start":4556.515,"stop":4559.739,"duration":3.22},{"text":"There's not prohibition against anything else.","start":4559.739,"stop":4561.441,"duration":1.7},{"text":"You just says this, you can't do it in such a way as to obstruct or unreasonably interfere with ingress and egress to the entrance of this building.","start":4561.441,"stop":4573.135,"duration":11.69},{"text":"That's all --","start":4573.135,"stop":4573.28,"duration":0.14}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, as I understand it, your record shows that they have parades that blocked the whole street so that people cannot -- cannot get in or out of the -- out of the courthouse and that the sanction that is permitted under this statute --","start":4573.28,"stop":4588.073,"duration":14.79}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"No --","start":4588.073,"stop":4588.321,"duration":0.25}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- but those are -- some people go with some signs saying that people in Mississippi are citizens also, that it's selectively enforced.","start":4588.321,"stop":4601.166,"duration":12.85}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":4601.166,"stop":4601.492,"duration":0.33},{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, for a group of people to parade down the public street of Hattiesburg and pass in front of the courthouse is a matter to be controlled by the City of Hattiesburg.","start":4601.492,"stop":4617.744,"duration":16.25},{"text":"Now, that's a different situation from -- that would keep you from going across the street, to get across that street over here.","start":4617.744,"stop":4632.894,"duration":15.15},{"text":"That's all for a short length of time, just to parade there should not keep them and this statute has nothing to do with that one way or the other.","start":4632.894,"stop":4640.18,"duration":7.29},{"text":"But this statute says this, you can't --","start":4640.18,"stop":4641.702,"duration":1.52}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"But you said -- you told us that there was no regulation on -- on whatsoever, on parades and on anybody and then in numbers that they wanted or for any purpose if they wanted, could parade -- parade throughout the streets of Hattiesburg and this record shows that they do not enforce that even though the streets are blocked so people can't get across to the courthouse.","start":4641.702,"stop":4667.826,"duration":26.12}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"The only question is that the record said this, does that parade pass in front of the courthouse?","start":4667.826,"stop":4671.766,"duration":3.94},{"text":"Yes.","start":4671.766,"stop":4672.137,"duration":0.37},{"text":"Could people get from across over the Beacon Street while the parade is passing by?","start":4672.137,"stop":4675.52,"duration":3.38},{"text":"He said, no.","start":4675.52,"stop":4676.413,"duration":0.89},{"text":"For a minute, they could.","start":4676.413,"stop":4678.157,"duration":1.74},{"text":"Just five minutes the parade goes by and they can come across the street.","start":4678.157,"stop":4682.687,"duration":4.53},{"text":"But that's not the -- that's not all on the courthouse.","start":4682.687,"stop":4687.825,"duration":5.14},{"text":"This courthouse sits sort of in the middle of the square.","start":4687.825,"stop":4692.423,"duration":4.6},{"text":"Streets come in and out of its way from this one.","start":4692.423,"stop":4694.854,"duration":2.43},{"text":"I think he's been the streets in Hattiesburg with stalls and so forth on it outside and the only thing this thing would prohibit there is this, don't demonstrate in such ways as to block or to obstruct or interfere with these entrances.","start":4694.854,"stop":4710.427,"duration":15.57}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose the parade that had started up and down the streets would have stopped in front of the courthouse and blocked the entrances, would it be barred?","start":4710.427,"stop":4719.704,"duration":9.28}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"I think the sheriff would have the right to go out there, yes sir, and enforce the statute on them.","start":4719.704,"stop":4724.227,"duration":4.52},{"text":"They would have the right.","start":4724.227,"stop":4725.223,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"And arrest them?","start":4725.223,"stop":4727.81,"duration":2.59}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"If they insisted on staying right there and would prevent them from getting there, I think he would have that right to charge them, yes.","start":4727.81,"stop":4735.33,"duration":7.52},{"text":"This is, as Mr. Justice Black said, just stop there.","start":4735.33,"stop":4738.192,"duration":2.86}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"What exactly --","start":4738.192,"stop":4739.202,"duration":1.01}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"There had to be some rule of reason.","start":4739.202,"stop":4740.182,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"If the marchers leaves and stop there, he'd arrest them?","start":4740.182,"stop":4744.509,"duration":4.33}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think he would.","start":4744.509,"stop":4745.329,"duration":0.82},{"text":"No, sir.","start":4745.329,"stop":4746.803,"duration":1.47},{"text":"And I think if a civil rights group stopped there, he would not arrest them either at the streets.","start":4746.803,"stop":4750.181,"duration":3.38}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"You're not in complete agreement on that.","start":4750.181,"stop":4755.208,"duration":5.03}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice Marshall, situations have changed dramatically in Mississippi, sir, since you were last there, I am happy to say.","start":4755.208,"stop":4766.178,"duration":10.97}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"It was a month or so when I was last there.","start":4766.178,"stop":4768.565,"duration":2.39}]},{"speakerName":"Will S. Wells","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, they changed then -- they had changed even then, if you were there a month or so ago since you were a long time ago sir, considerably so.","start":4768.565,"stop":4778.99,"duration":10.43},{"text":"And I'd like to say that I have done what I can as the assistant attorney general to help change -- I've done my best to have -- even Judge Rives complimented me when I before the Fifth Circuit recently but in fact, he said you all had done a good job in Mississippi a whole lot better than we are in Alabama and I think some of the -- some of it -- you were entitled to create some of it.","start":4778.99,"stop":4808.366,"duration":29.38},{"text":"Mr. Wells and I rather appreciate it even though he wrote the dissent in this case.","start":4808.366,"stop":4817.248,"duration":8.88}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - March 05, 1968","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren15/oral_argument_audio/15548","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Number 699, John Earl Cameron et al., appellant, versus Paul Johnson et al.","start":0,"stop":49.6,"duration":49.6},{"text":"Mr. Kinoy -- Mr. Smith, you may proceed with your argument.","start":49.6,"stop":55.321,"duration":5.72}]},{"speakerName":"Benjamin E. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":55.321,"stop":59.13,"duration":3.81},{"text":"The District Court below in this matter was directed by this Court per curiam in 1966 to reconsider this matter.","start":59.13,"stop":77.839,"duration":18.71},{"text":"This is a -- an injunction case brought in the Southern District of Mississippi heard before a three-judge court.","start":77.839,"stop":87.331,"duration":9.49},{"text":"The three-judge court decided that the injunction should not issue.","start":87.331,"stop":91.276,"duration":3.94},{"text":"They appealed that to this Court and this Court noted probable jurisdiction and sent the matter back to the three-judge District Court of the Southern District of Mississippi with instructions that the per curiam -- with instructions that the issuance of the injunction requested to halt state prosecutions of civil rights workers should be considered in one; whether or not Title 28 Section 2283 the writ prohibition, the injunction prohibition statute apply and secondly; whether or not the injunction should issue by virtue of the meeting of the criteria set forth by this Court in the Dombrowski case.","start":91.276,"stop":132.353,"duration":41.08},{"text":"This Court therefore is familiar with the case.","start":132.353,"stop":134.838,"duration":2.48},{"text":"This is the second time it's been here.","start":134.838,"stop":137.292,"duration":2.45},{"text":"Briefly, the injunction was filed in April 1964.","start":137.292,"stop":141.068,"duration":3.78},{"text":"First judge hearing -- the three-judge hearing was in July of that year.","start":141.068,"stop":145.125,"duration":4.06},{"text":"This Court's first opinion was in July of 1965.","start":145.125,"stop":149.209,"duration":4.08},{"text":"We retried the case in October and it was decided -- October 1965 and it was decided by the three-judge court in December 1966.","start":149.209,"stop":157.654,"duration":8.44},{"text":"There are approximately 51 or 55 state criminal proceedings pending and it's based upon a statute.","start":157.654,"stop":163.27,"duration":5.62},{"text":"They are based upon a statute which forbids blocking the ingress and egress, unreasonably blocking the ingress and egress to courthouses in Mississippi.","start":163.27,"stop":175.944,"duration":12.67},{"text":"I will discuss the 2283 problem.","start":175.944,"stop":178.968,"duration":3.02},{"text":"My colleague, Mr. Kinoy will discuss the case as the facts relate to the Dombrowski case.","start":178.968,"stop":184.529,"duration":5.56},{"text":"Basically, we take the position that 2283 of Title 28 is not a jurisdictional statute.","start":184.529,"stop":192.711,"duration":8.18},{"text":"It is a comity statute.","start":192.711,"stop":194.878,"duration":2.17},{"text":"It cannot prevent the issuance of the injunction or the consideration of the injunction sought in this case.","start":194.878,"stop":202.951,"duration":8.07},{"text":"Judge Rives, Circuit Judge Rives below who was one of the members of the three-judge court agreed with us in this regard.","start":202.951,"stop":210.931,"duration":7.98},{"text":"He said simply very quickly on, “I would hold” and this is on page 60 of the transcript, “I would hold that under the circumstances of this case, if the allegations are approved, Section 1983 which is the basis for the injunction suits sought below, Section 1983 is an express exception to Section 2283.”","start":210.931,"stop":235.532,"duration":24.6},{"text":"And he says again, “The principles rationally extrapolated from the cases creating express exceptions to the prohibition of Section 2283 derive content from the concrete situations which gave rise to them.","start":235.532,"stop":253.097,"duration":17.56},{"text":"Where a specific, limited and clearly delineated substantive right has been conferred by Congress, the courts have found an express exception to Section 2283.","start":253.097,"stop":263.461,"duration":10.36},{"text":"The express exception is the necessary co-commitment of the need to vindicate federally created rights and is entirely consistent with the history of Section 2283.","start":263.461,"stop":273.339,"duration":9.88},{"text":"That appears on section -- on page 63 of the record.","start":273.339,"stop":277.463,"duration":4.12},{"text":"Now, we take the position Your Honors that this is a comity statute, that is Section 2283 is a comity statute, that it has to be understood and explained and utilized in a comity situation.","start":277.463,"stop":293.213,"duration":15.75},{"text":"What was meant when Section 1983 was drawn up by the reconstruction Congress, it meant that these federally -- given federally determined rights were going to be used to protect the newly freed slaves, that they were going to be used to vindicate federal rights and Federal Courts in the southern states.","start":293.213,"stop":317.772,"duration":24.56},{"text":"And that Section 1983 was going to see to it that the Fourteenth Amendment was fully implemented, fully carried out and it gave equitable relief under 1983 to the individual suitor, to individuals who could come in and ask for an injunction, and that's what the individual suitor is doing here.","start":317.772,"stop":335.96,"duration":18.19},{"text":"These people in Mississippi were involved in a voter registration drive and you can see from the pictures in the record, they were walking around the courthouse with signs that said, “Mississippians are Americans, too.","start":335.96,"stop":347.873,"duration":11.91},{"text":"We want the right to vote,” entirely, completely, utterly peaceful demonstration.","start":347.873,"stop":353.487,"duration":5.61}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that the issue before the passing Civil Rights Act?","start":353.487,"stop":356.848,"duration":3.36}]},{"speakerName":"Benjamin E. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":356.848,"stop":357.479,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":357.479,"stop":359.681,"duration":2.2}]},{"speakerName":"Benjamin E. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"The voting act as well as the one of 1964, too, Mr. Justice Harlan.","start":359.681,"stop":365.426,"duration":5.75},{"text":"But what we're saying is that these were federal rights that they were trying to protect.","start":365.426,"stop":371.042,"duration":5.62},{"text":"They were really talking in terms of Section 1971 and then later Section 1973(b)(i) or (i)(b) of the Voting Rights Act.","start":371.042,"stop":382.954,"duration":11.91},{"text":"And they were trying I think -- of course, it's pretty obvious what they were trying to do, they're trying to get people to register vote, but there is just as much reason for saying that Section 1971 gives these people an expressly authorized congressional authority to come in and ask for this injunction as it is to say Section 2038 of the Voting Rights Act has the same thing attached to it.","start":382.954,"stop":409.742,"duration":26.79},{"text":"And we also know that -- for example, when this Court decided the Rachel case.","start":409.742,"stop":416.207,"duration":6.46},{"text":"They decided it's of Title 2 of the Public Accommodations.","start":416.207,"stop":419.865,"duration":3.66},{"text":"They gave an actual thrust, in other words, the positive requirement that there have been injunction sought or there be relief sought, this authorized removal.","start":419.865,"stop":430.484,"duration":10.62},{"text":"Well, here this Court by turning down certiorari in the Hamer versus Campell case where there was an injunction sought and overturning of election, here was a private citizen coming in under 1983 and other related statutes, attempting to exert a right and here, you didn't hold that 2283 was a ban.","start":430.484,"stop":452.593,"duration":22.11},{"text":"2283 cannot be a ban in this case.","start":452.593,"stop":455.558,"duration":2.96},{"text":"If 2283 comes into play, it cannot come into play in this situation simply because if the criteria set forth in Dombrowski are met, well then this isn't expressly an authorized exception to the case.","start":455.558,"stop":478.49,"duration":22.93},{"text":"The whole thrust of the case for example in Potter versus Dixon, in Rachel and in US versus Woods and all those cases we're citing in the brief, the Court has every time made an exception and said this is an expressly authorized exception to 2283.","start":478.49,"stop":496.023,"duration":17.53},{"text":"You can come in and file these injunction proceedings.","start":496.023,"stop":501.014,"duration":4.99},{"text":"I think it's very clear that that's exactly what they were talking about here.","start":501.014,"stop":506.084,"duration":5.07},{"text":"The other -- my opponent, Mr. Wells in his brief talks about the Baines case being a bar and that's Baines versus City of Danville, but when that case was decided, this Court had not come down with a Dombrowski hearing yet and was pretty clear that the same judge who wrote the Baines opinion, later on came out and talked in terms of Dombrowski which was now then available to him in the case of Unites Steel Workers of America versus Bagwell which is 383 Federal Reporter 2nd the September 1967 case in which he says on page 495 the abstention doctrine warrants refusal to exercise properly invoked federal jurisdiction to adjudicate the constitutionality of the state statute.","start":506.084,"stop":553.363,"duration":47.28},{"text":"If there is any doubt about the statute's applicability to the challenger or to his conduct and when construction of the statute by the state courts may remove the constitutional issue from the case.","start":553.363,"stop":563.891,"duration":10.53},{"text":"When however the statute is obviously applicable to the plaintiff in the course of conduct that when the statute is not susceptible to a construction that will otherwise avoid the necessity of deciding the constitutional question, a Federal Court may not properly state its hand.","start":563.891,"stop":579.239,"duration":15.35},{"text":"So really what we're saying here is that we're not so much in exception, expressly authorized by the Congress but where you have the federally given rights as you do in Section 1983 of Title 42, you have a positive federal burden and duty to step in and issue the injunction to protect the issuance of -- to protect those rights so that 1983 is not a bar.","start":579.239,"stop":608.571,"duration":29.33},{"text":"It is a positive statement under the theory of comity that there has to be a right on the part of either the federal government or the individual litigant to go forward and issue the injunction or to hold the hearing and see if the injunction should issue.","start":608.571,"stop":629.661,"duration":21.09},{"text":"This was made all the more clear when this Court decided the Peacock case because when Mr. Justice Stewart wrote the decision in Peacock in a portion of the opinion as this Court well knows, denying the right of removal in that case, he said in effect and I don't need to quote it, that there should be -- there will be other remedies available and one of these other remedies alluded to by Mr. Justice Stewart in that Peacock opinion was the remedy of injunction.","start":629.661,"stop":661.464,"duration":31.8},{"text":"Now, this is the remedy we're seeking here.","start":661.464,"stop":663.553,"duration":2.09},{"text":"I say to you gentlemen here now, we've lost the removal in Peacock.","start":663.553,"stop":668.764,"duration":5.21},{"text":"We can no longer -- the situation in the south is still bad.","start":668.764,"stop":672.317,"duration":3.55},{"text":"There is no question about it.","start":672.317,"stop":674.326,"duration":2.01},{"text":"In voting situations, there is still violence going on.","start":674.326,"stop":678.802,"duration":4.48},{"text":"There are shootings going on, and we know that there were some last night in front of (Inaudible) house down there in Mississippi a shotgun went off.","start":678.802,"stop":687.187,"duration":8.38},{"text":"We still have a voting problem down there.","start":687.187,"stop":690.077,"duration":2.89},{"text":"I don't care how many acts you're going to pass, you're still are going to have this problem and we still need some protection.","start":690.077,"stop":696.478,"duration":6.4},{"text":"We didn't get it in Peacock but we're back now down to the bottom of the barrel.","start":696.478,"stop":702.104,"duration":5.63},{"text":"If we don't get it with the injunction procedure, we're going to be in serious trouble down there.","start":702.104,"stop":709.231,"duration":7.13},{"text":"What you're saying -- alright, I can understand how you would feel about removal when a lawyer can come in and simply file a removal petition and he ties up the docket of the Federal Court, the Court has to hold a hearing.","start":709.231,"stop":721.77,"duration":12.54},{"text":"And I think Mr. Justice White was talking about that when we argued Peacock about the problems involved.","start":721.77,"stop":726.638,"duration":4.87},{"text":"But here, you have a more precise remedy available to you.","start":726.638,"stop":729.917,"duration":3.28},{"text":"You have an injunction proceeding which is a more delicate remedy.","start":729.917,"stop":734.261,"duration":4.34},{"text":"It's one that will only tie up the federal courts and their dockets if the judge, after hearing or looking at the case feels that he's got something that ought to be looked into.","start":734.261,"stop":744.109,"duration":9.85},{"text":"Does it meet the Dombrowski criteria?","start":744.109,"stop":748.114,"duration":4},{"text":"The whole situation would be -- I think would resolve itself differently.","start":748.114,"stop":753.106,"duration":4.99}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Smith, what would be the issues in the injunction suit?","start":753.106,"stop":757.928,"duration":4.82},{"text":"I know that Mr. Kinoy is going to talk about Dombrowski but would that be -- would the question be whether the defendants in the state proceeding had violated the state statute?","start":757.928,"stop":771.236,"duration":13.31},{"text":"Would that play a part in it?","start":771.236,"stop":773.373,"duration":2.14}]},{"speakerName":"Benjamin E. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"No sir, I don't think that --","start":773.373,"stop":774.353,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Or would it just be whether the state statute is unconstitutional on its face, would there be any factual issues -- would any factual issues be relevant?","start":774.353,"stop":786.054,"duration":11.7}]},{"speakerName":"Benjamin E. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"I think factual issues would be relevant.","start":786.054,"stop":788.141,"duration":2.09},{"text":"I don't think the question of guilt or innocence would be the relevant issue, Mr. Justice Fortas.","start":788.141,"stop":792.73,"duration":4.59},{"text":"I think first of all, the constitutionality of the statute on its face would be an important threshold question.","start":792.73,"stop":799.429,"duration":6.7},{"text":"Secondly, I think that we find that -- I think even in the per curiam remand dissent that Mr. Justice Black wrote in this case, he said that if it was a valid statute and it was being enforced to harass somebody, well then that would be a proper fit -- subject for the hearing, too.","start":799.429,"stop":814.667,"duration":15.24}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"And going beyond that, suppose the Federal Court or District Court decided that it was not unconstitutional on its face and it's not being used to what I'd call for brief of Dombrowski way to harass people.","start":814.667,"stop":832.358,"duration":17.69},{"text":"Does the Court go on to find out whether it was improperly applied or unconstitutionally applied –","start":832.358,"stop":843.046,"duration":10.69}]},{"speakerName":"Benjamin E. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"Surely.","start":843.046,"stop":843.379,"duration":0.33},{"text":"I think you use --","start":843.379,"stop":844.206,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"-- separate things?","start":844.206,"stop":845.235,"duration":1.03}]},{"speakerName":"Benjamin E. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"-- I think you'd use the whole question of selective enforcement, Mr. Justice Fortas.","start":845.235,"stop":849.59,"duration":4.36}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"But would those two things be involved as you said, whether the statute was being improperly applied to people who have been really violated?","start":849.59,"stop":859.691,"duration":10.1}]},{"speakerName":"Benjamin E. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":859.691,"stop":860.467,"duration":0.78},{"text":"Yes, I think that that would be involved in it, just as it was in Dombrowski.","start":860.467,"stop":866.234,"duration":5.77}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I'm not sure there was in Dombrowski, maybe, but in any event, what you're saying then is that we're really trying a criminal case on the equity side of the court?","start":866.234,"stop":877.683,"duration":11.45}]},{"speakerName":"Benjamin E. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":877.683,"stop":878.622,"duration":0.94},{"text":"I think that that's what's the situation is.","start":878.622,"stop":879.587,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"That's about right.","start":879.587,"stop":880.866,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"Benjamin E. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":880.866,"stop":881.613,"duration":0.75},{"text":"That's -- if you look at the record, that's about what we did -- what we did here.","start":881.613,"stop":884.412,"duration":2.8}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand.","start":884.412,"stop":885.245,"duration":0.83},{"text":"I had a look at the record and I understand what you're doing --","start":885.245,"stop":886.9,"duration":1.65}]},{"speakerName":"Benjamin E. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, I'm sorry.","start":886.9,"stop":887.334,"duration":0.43},{"text":"I didn't mean to imply that --","start":887.334,"stop":889,"duration":1.67}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"-- trying to get your view of it as a matter of theory.","start":889,"stop":892.863,"duration":3.86},{"text":"For example, in this case, an issue in the injunction proceeding would be whether these people did or didn't, might be that the Court got passed preliminary constitutional question, whether these people did or did not block access to the courthouse?","start":892.863,"stop":909.497,"duration":16.63}]},{"speakerName":"Benjamin E. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, that would -- that would be part of it.","start":909.497,"stop":912.133,"duration":2.64},{"text":"I think I said in the removal petition that I draft -- I mean the injunction that I drafted, I think I did put in there, Mr. Justice Fortas, that they were not guilty of what they were charged.","start":912.133,"stop":925.835,"duration":13.7},{"text":"But the question I think basically on the hearing would be whether the statute was being used to harass this civil rights work because that's fundamentally the basic question and it becomes a lot easier to determine where there is harassment if one goes into the statute itself.","start":925.835,"stop":940.637,"duration":14.8},{"text":"I think Mr. Kinoy is going to develop that, but you can see if you have an invalid statute how funny it looks to try to enforce it many times and I think that shows up in this record, too.","start":940.637,"stop":949.817,"duration":9.18},{"text":"So that when you have these criteria here, I think you got such a very strong thrust behind the whole question of federal rights, that this question 2283 just passes right out the window.","start":949.817,"stop":959.665,"duration":9.85},{"text":"And really, if you read Judge Rives' dissenting opinion in the second hearing, that is the one in 1965 which came down to 1966, you'll see that that's really -- he says the threshold question merges into the large question immediately.","start":959.665,"stop":973.204,"duration":13.54},{"text":"He says if you have alleged and can show the Dombrowksi type criteria, he thinks the foundation for the issuance of the injunction is there and the exception under 2283 is already brought into existence so that --","start":973.204,"stop":985,"duration":11.8}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you arguing at all, Mr. Smith, that in any event, the declaratory judgment -- this federal district court should have given you declaratory judgment on the constitutional question?","start":985,"stop":997.201,"duration":12.2}]},{"speakerName":"Benjamin E. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"No sir, I don't think --","start":997.201,"stop":997.791,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Apart from the injunction?","start":997.791,"stop":1001.287,"duration":3.5},{"text":"I mean, the sort of thing that we dealt with in Cuder (ph).","start":1001.287,"stop":1004.794,"duration":3.51}]},{"speakerName":"Benjamin E. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"In Cooper?","start":1004.794,"stop":1005.639,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Cuder --","start":1005.639,"stop":1006.367,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"Benjamin E. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"Cuder, oh yes, that was the one I was reading here.","start":1006.367,"stop":1012.355,"duration":5.99},{"text":"I would say a declaratory judgment would be as effective in holding -- in stopping the prosecutions, which is what we're looking at here, I would think.","start":1012.355,"stop":1022.912,"duration":10.56}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if that's so, then why do you get involved with 2283 at all in Dombrowski or Dombrowski --?","start":1022.912,"stop":1035.354,"duration":12.44}]},{"speakerName":"Benjamin E. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, of course I guess we're there because after the original petition --","start":1035.354,"stop":1038.462,"duration":3.11}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, you better be -- if you better be there, you should be in the Court of Appeals.","start":1038.462,"stop":1042.38,"duration":3.92}]},{"speakerName":"Benjamin E. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"Right, right, I agree.","start":1042.38,"stop":1044.652,"duration":2.27},{"text":"I'm just simply saying when I drafted my original papers in the three-judge court, Mr. Justice Brennan, I made it a petition for an injunction and a class action followed by amendment.","start":1044.652,"stop":1055.169,"duration":10.52},{"text":"I didn't ask as I recall -- now I'm looking at the pleadings in this regard, I don't believe I asked for a declaratory judgment.","start":1055.169,"stop":1060.789,"duration":5.62},{"text":"I asked for an injunction against the prosecution that of course I later removed them in that --","start":1060.789,"stop":1065.611,"duration":4.82}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But you do suggest that perhaps the declaratory judgment in these circumstances might be of great service to you?","start":1065.611,"stop":1073.668,"duration":8.06}]},{"speakerName":"Benjamin E. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"It might be of service to me.","start":1073.668,"stop":1074.832,"duration":1.16},{"text":"I don't know that --","start":1074.832,"stop":1075.651,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Cuder indicates that perhaps the Federal Court in any event ought to proceed to give it a declaratory judgment?","start":1075.651,"stop":1082.712,"duration":7.06}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That is if it's -- if it's -- at least it it's on the face attack?","start":1082.712,"stop":1087.985,"duration":5.27}]},{"speakerName":"Benjamin E. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, yes.","start":1087.985,"stop":1088.823,"duration":0.84},{"text":"I don't know what the effect would be.","start":1088.823,"stop":1090.869,"duration":2.05},{"text":"I guess the effect would naturally be to stop the prosecutions because they wouldn't have a statute under which they could prosecute.","start":1090.869,"stop":1098.208,"duration":7.34}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"If you get a declaratory judgment of unconstitutionality on its face, I expect that the defense of the prosecution if they proceeded with it, you wouldn't be badly off, would you?","start":1098.208,"stop":1109.802,"duration":11.59}]},{"speakerName":"Benjamin E. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"I think it would be alright.","start":1109.802,"stop":1112.137,"duration":2.34}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"In Jeannette, this Court refused to authorize an injunction even though the statute had been declared unconstitutional that very day.","start":1112.137,"stop":1123.848,"duration":11.71},{"text":"Now, let's assume that there was a declaratory judgment action in the District Court brought by you.","start":1123.848,"stop":1130.692,"duration":6.84},{"text":"There's a declaration that the statute is unconstitutional.","start":1130.692,"stop":1134.538,"duration":3.85},{"text":"At that point, would there be any reason for entering an injunction against the state court?","start":1134.538,"stop":1143.567,"duration":9.03}]},{"speakerName":"Benjamin E. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1143.567,"stop":1143.774,"duration":0.21},{"text":"I guess what happened in Jeanette was in effect of the injunction.","start":1143.774,"stop":1149.592,"duration":5.82},{"text":"Since it happened the same day, really it wouldn't have to happen at the same day.","start":1149.592,"stop":1153.129,"duration":3.54},{"text":"But no, I hadn't thought about it in those -- in that sense, Mr. Justice White, but I can see where it would a declaratory judgment, particularly where you have a statute that is facially unconstitutional as we've alleged in this case.","start":1153.129,"stop":1166.317,"duration":13.19},{"text":"If you're dealing with a statute that's going to be facially correct, but is being utilized in another fashion --","start":1166.317,"stop":1175.689,"duration":9.37}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But your challenge here is facially to this --","start":1175.689,"stop":1179.31,"duration":3.62}]},{"speakerName":"Benjamin E. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, we went both routes.","start":1179.31,"stop":1181.683,"duration":2.37},{"text":"We went both routes on it.","start":1181.683,"stop":1184.248,"duration":2.57},{"text":"And -- well actually, the American Law Institute has addressed itself to this whole question, in their tentative draft number five which they considered last May.","start":1184.248,"stop":1201.335,"duration":17.09},{"text":"They talked in terms of what changes were brought in this section, in the area of the law by the Peacock decision, and Rachel as well, and they were the ones that came up in their commentary on pages 112 and 113 that talk about the whole business of strengthening the government's or the person's or the individual litigant's right to bring the injunction and the whole idea that 2283 is not a bar to the bringing of the injunction.","start":1201.335,"stop":1247.134,"duration":45.8},{"text":"I would think, Your Honors, in the situation that we have here, the facts are going to show that the criteria set forth in the opinion written by you, Mr. Justice Brennan, are met and when they're met, then there should be an injunction issue.","start":1247.134,"stop":1269.827,"duration":22.69},{"text":"The whole question or the issue of the injunction should then come up.","start":1269.827,"stop":1272.224,"duration":2.4},{"text":"It should not bar the courts to these injunctions.","start":1272.224,"stop":1275.6,"duration":3.38},{"text":"If we don't have the injunction, the only thing left for us is habeas.","start":1275.6,"stop":1278.929,"duration":3.33},{"text":"We've lost in -- with removal.","start":1278.929,"stop":1280.952,"duration":2.02},{"text":"We've got to some way protect these federally constitutional, federally protected, federally defined rights.","start":1280.952,"stop":1289.271,"duration":8.32},{"text":"And injunction, as far as I can see I guess along with the discussion of the panel on declaratory judgment is just about all that's left in many of these situations and I thank you gentlemen.","start":1289.271,"stop":1304.304,"duration":15.03}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Kinoy?","start":1304.304,"stop":1306,"duration":1.7}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, Your Honor, may it please the Court.","start":1306,"stop":1309.736,"duration":3.74},{"text":"With the time I have left, I'll start the argument, with the permission of the Court, I would like to turn to what we regard as the basic issue in this case or as Judge Rives has put it in his opinion, the only real issue in this case and that is whether the facts as proved require the granting of the injunctive relief requested.","start":1309.736,"stop":1333.39,"duration":23.65},{"text":"Or as this Court put it in the second question in the remand to the District Court whether the injunctive relief is appropriate in light of the criteria set forth in Dombrowski.","start":1333.39,"stop":1345.307,"duration":11.92},{"text":"For as Mr. Smith has argued here and as Judge Rives put so succinctly in his opinion, the essence of the 2283 problem is that the principles of comity which are codified in 2283 embody the concept of the primacy of the federal courts in protecting fundamental federal rights expressed in the 1871 Act, now of course 1983 which this Court developed soulfully in this (Inaudible) decision in this term.","start":1345.307,"stop":1388.596,"duration":43.29},{"text":"If those criteria are met, then the fundamental principles which govern the federal system require not sanction but require the granting of the injunctive relief.","start":1388.596,"stop":1405.844,"duration":17.25},{"text":"Now, the approach to this fundamental question I would suggest to the Court is governed by two main considerations.","start":1405.844,"stop":1417.266,"duration":11.42},{"text":"This case for the first time comes to this Court bottomed fully upon an evidentiary record and an evidentiary record fully tried which the appellees -- which Mississippi now concedes that with two relatively minor exceptions, our statement of facts in the brief are generally correct and I call the Court's attention to the appellee's brief in this respect.","start":1417.266,"stop":1457.559,"duration":40.29},{"text":"Now, we suggest this is a rather unusual concession by appellees because the statement of facts which emerged from the evidentiary hearing presents the issue to this Court in the following matrix of events.","start":1457.559,"stop":1477.227,"duration":19.67},{"text":"The following fundamental conclusions of fact upon which the Dombrowski criteria flowed.","start":1477.227,"stop":1485.086,"duration":7.86},{"text":"First; the demonstrations which continued over a period of four months or for the purpose of protesting discrimination against Negro citizens in voting and encouraging Negro citizens to register to vote were at all times entirely peaceful, conceded by Mississippi.","start":1485.086,"stop":1509.354,"duration":24.27},{"text":"Secondly, that the demonstrators at all times remained within the express area designated originally by the law enforcement officers who had themselves selected that area so that the demonstrators, when marching, would not obstruct access to the courthouse, conceded by Mississippi.","start":1509.354,"stop":1540.573,"duration":31.22},{"text":"Third; that this statute has been selectively enforced so as to arrest only persons engaged in these activities, conceded by Mississippi.","start":1540.573,"stop":1559.011,"duration":18.44},{"text":"Now, I suggest to the Court that the first decisive fact which emerges from the evidentiary hearing upon which this Court must judge the criteria of Dombrowski is that the statute has admittedly and open, been selectively enforced in the area of First Amendment rights.","start":1559.011,"stop":1588.259,"duration":29.25},{"text":"Now, the facts of selective enforcement uncontested and testified to by Mississippi state authorities at the hearing is exactly parallel to the situation this Court faced in Cox against Louisiana.","start":1588.259,"stop":1608.544,"duration":20.29},{"text":"The testimony of the country prosecuting attorney, Mr. Dukes, which is set forth in page 74 of our brief for the Court's convenience was that parades which block the streets and obstruct traffic are permitted in Hattiesburg and have been permitted by arrangements with the city officials and that there are no standards in the statute or anywhere else for determination by the officials as to which demonstration to permit, that there are no permit procedures and no standards.","start":1608.544,"stop":1655.861,"duration":47.32},{"text":"Now, as this Court said in Cox both in the majority and in the concurring opinions, this situation is the clear equivalent of a statute which permits officials to act as a censor and that the pervasive restraint upon freedom of expression, or as this Court put it in Dombrowski, the chilling effect upon the expression of First Amendment rights is not any less effective than a statute which expressly permits such selective enforcement.","start":1655.861,"stop":1700.157,"duration":44.3},{"text":"Now, what I suggest to the Court is so shocking here on this hearing, is that the testimony admittedly adduced by the Mississippi officials vividly illustrates the constitutional evil in selective enforcement which this Court has condemned from Edwards to Cox and which every member of this Court has adhered to whether in its dissenting opinions or majority opinions, that this constitutional evil is embraced by the appellees and the majority below as the very justification for this selective enforcement.","start":1700.157,"stop":1749.585,"duration":49.43}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask you a question?","start":1749.585,"stop":1750.264,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Mr. Justice Black.","start":1750.264,"stop":1751.782,"duration":1.52}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You said, which I remember this Court has dissented.","start":1751.782,"stop":1757.626,"duration":5.84},{"text":"Do I understand you to say that every member of this Court has conceded that a state is without power, constitutional power to prevent people marching round and round the building on the street?","start":1757.626,"stop":1773.849,"duration":16.22}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"Definitely not, Your Honor, no.","start":1773.849,"stop":1775.917,"duration":2.07},{"text":"This Court is sharply split on this question, let that question open in Cox and Your Honor has expressed yourself very strongly on that issue.","start":1775.917,"stop":1784.433,"duration":8.52},{"text":"This Court however and Your Honor in Cox and Your Honor dissenting in Brown-Louisiana and Your Honor writing the majority in Adderley has said at a minimum, there must be evenhanded application of a state statute.","start":1784.433,"stop":1803.16,"duration":18.73},{"text":"This testimony shows concededly that there has not been evenhanded application.","start":1803.16,"stop":1811.536,"duration":8.38},{"text":"If the majority of this court in Adderley is to be followed in this case, this statute must be restrained because concededly, Mississippi has stated in open hearing that the statute has not been evenhandedly enforced and they explained why.","start":1811.536,"stop":1836.722,"duration":25.19}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose it has not, what is the relief you ask?","start":1836.722,"stop":1839.808,"duration":3.09}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"We ask for injunctive relief against the pending criminal prosecutions which are part of a prosecutorial plan, Mr. Justice White's words in the dissenting opinion in Cameron itself, part of a plan of a prosecutor to misuse this statute.","start":1839.808,"stop":1863.333,"duration":23.53},{"text":"Selective enforcement, I suggest to the Court, is the classic example of a prosecutor's misuse of a statute.","start":1863.333,"stop":1874.915,"duration":11.58},{"text":"Now, Judge Coleman below for the majority explained that of course there was this selective enforcement, but it was alright.","start":1874.915,"stop":1886.239,"duration":11.32},{"text":"Why?","start":1886.239,"stop":1887.841,"duration":1.6},{"text":"Because he says here in this case, we are not dealing with parades carried on by common consent on the public streets.","start":1887.841,"stop":1899.956,"duration":12.12},{"text":"And Mr. Wells, the attorney -- assistant attorney general of Mississippi at the hearing stated that the critical difference between those activities, Your Honor, which admittedly violated the statute, obstructed the streets like the parades, and those activities of our clients, the Black citizens of Mississippi and their White supporters, the critical difference was that they were a different type of activity.","start":1899.956,"stop":1931.041,"duration":31.09},{"text":"They had a different purpose.","start":1931.041,"stop":1934.809,"duration":3.77},{"text":"Now, I suggest to the Court that the position of the appellees and the majority below goes to the very heart of the First Amendment because this Court has taught that the First Amendment does not merely permit activities which the majority of a community approves of by common consent, that it put --","start":1934.809,"stop":1959.972,"duration":25.16}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"We will recess now.","start":1959.972,"stop":1961.336,"duration":1.36}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur Kinoy","textObjs":[{"text":"Certainly, Your Honor.","start":1961.336,"stop":1964.801,"duration":3.46}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Warren Court","arguedOn":"Mar  5 - 6, 1968","petitioner":"","respondent":"","docket":"699","citation":"390 US 611 (1968)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/390/611","lowerCourt":"","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"Apr 22, 1968"}